# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: endangered-species-act-of-1973
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] The **103rd United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] It met in Washington, D.C. from January 3, 1993, to January 3, 1995, during the final weeks of George H.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Bush's presidency and in the first two years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1990 United States census.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress to have a Democratic senator from Texas, Bob Krueger, who lost election to finish Lloyd Bentsen's term in 1993.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Along with two Democratic senators from the state of Tennessee, Jim Sasser and Harlan Mathews.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Jim Sasser lost re-election and Harlan Mathews retired in 1994.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] In addition, a Democratic senator from the state of Oklahoma, David Boren, resigned in the final weeks of the Congress.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Both chambers maintained a Democratic majority, and with Bill Clinton being sworn in as president on January 20, 1993, this gave the Democrats an overall federal government trifecta for the first time since the 96th Congress in 1979.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p01] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p02] Lists of committees and their party leaders for members of the House and Senate committees can be found through the Official Congressional Directory at the bottom of this article.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p02] The directory after the pages of terms of service lists committees of the Senate, House (Standing with Subcommittees, Select and Special) and Joint and, after that, House/Senate committee assignments.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/103rd-united-states-congress-p02] On the committees section of the House and Senate in the Official Congressional Directory, the committee's members on the first row on the left side shows the chairman of the committee and on the right side shows the ranking member of the committee.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/104th-united-states-congress] The **104th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/104th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C. from January 3, 1995, to January 3, 1997, during the third and fourth years of Bill Clinton's presidency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/104th-united-states-congress] Apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1990 United States census.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/104th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had Republican majorities for the first time since the 83rd Congress in 1953.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/104th-united-states-congress] Major events included passage of elements of the Contract with America and a budget impasse between Congress and the Clinton administration that resulted in the federal government shutdown of 1995 and 1996.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/104th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1996; Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1998; and Class 1 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring re-election in 2000.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/104th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The **118th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] It convened in Washington, D.C., on January 3, 2023, and ended on January 3, 2025, during the final two years of Joe Biden's presidency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] With Republicans winning the House, the 118th Congress ended the federal government trifecta Democrats held in the 117th.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] This congress also featured the first female Senate president pro tempore (Patty Murray), the first black party leader (Hakeem Jeffries) in congressional history, and the longest-serving Senate party leaders (Mitch McConnell and Dick Durbin).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The Senate had the highest number of Independent members in a single Congress since the ratification of the 17th Amendment after Joe Manchin left the Democratic Party to become an Independent.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The 118th Congress was characterized as a uniquely ineffectual Congress, with its most notable events pointing towards political dysfunction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] By August 2024, the Congress has passed only 78 laws, less than a third of the next lowest laws per Congress in the 112th Congress, which also featured a Republican House opposing the Democratic Senate and White House.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] This resulted in the need for a legislative coalition to pass key legislation, allowing the minority to exercise powers usually reserved for the majority.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The fractious session demotivated many veteran legislators, with five committee chairs among the dozens who declared their resignation or retirement before the end of the session, three of whom were eligible to reprise their positions if the Republican Party retained their majority for 2025.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] A higher-than-average number of retiring lawmakers were those attempting to pass bipartisan and collaborative legislation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Two complete discharge petitions were filed in late 2024, both Republican-led with majority Democratic support, demonstrating a trend towards bucking leadership and lack of party discipline; such a gambit was last successful in 2015 to support the Export–Import Bank.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The second of these, a bill to remove certain Social Security restrictions, was subject to an unusual legislative procedure when a chair pro forma called forth a motion to table on a bill while the chamber was empty, flouting House convention and agreements.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The Congress began with a multi-ballot election for Speaker of the House, which had not happened since the 68th Congress in 1923.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Kevin McCarthy was eventually elected speaker on the 15th ballot.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] After relying on bipartisan votes to get out of a debt ceiling crisis and government shutdown threats, McCarthy became the first speaker ever to be removed from the role during a legislative session on October 3, 2023.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Following three failed attempts by various representatives to fill the post, on October 25, Mike Johnson was elected as speaker.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Johnson would advance four more bipartisan continuing resolutions from November into March to avoid shutdowns.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Congress finalized the 2024 United States federal budget on March 23, 2024, through two separate minibus packages.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Following a contentious foreign-aid vote, a motion to remove Johnson from the speakership was defeated in a bipartisan vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Partisan disciplinary actions also increased.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] With the expulsion of New York representative George Santos from the House in December 2023, over the opposition of the speaker, this was the first congress since the 107th in which a member was expelled, and the first ever in which a Republican was.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] There was also an increase of censures passed in the House, being the first congress with multiple censures since the 1983 congressional page sex scandal and the most in one year since 1870.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] In December 2023, House Republicans authorized an impeachment inquiry into Joe Biden, followed by the impeachment of Alejandro Mayorkas in February 2024, the first time a cabinet secretary has been the target of impeachment proceedings since William W.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] Belknap in 1876, and only the second such cabinet impeachment in history.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] The charges were dismissed by the Senate, the first time the Senate dismissed impeachment articles without trial after the reading.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress with Democratic senators from the states of Montana (Jon Tester) and Ohio (Sherrod Brown), both of whom lost re-election in 2024.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p02] The numbers refer to their Senate classes.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p02] All class 3 seats were contested in the November 2022 elections.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p02] In this Congress, class 3 means their term commenced in 2023, requiring re-election in 2028; class 1 means their term ends with this Congress, requiring re-election in 2024; and class 2 means their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 2026.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p02] All 435 seats were filled by election in November 2022.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p02] Additionally, six non-voting members were elected from the American territories and Washington, D.C.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p02] The numbers refer to the congressional district of the given state in this Congress.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/118th-united-states-congress-p02] Eight new congressional districts were created or re-created, while eight others were eliminated, as a result of the 2020 United States census.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] An election for a seat in the United States House of Representatives took place in California's 12th congressional district on November 5, 1946, the date set by law for the elections for the 80th United States Congress.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the 12th district election, the candidates were five-term incumbent Democrat Jerry Voorhis, Republican challenger Richard Nixon, and former congressman and Prohibition Party candidate John Hoeppel.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was elected with 56% of the vote, starting him on the road that would, almost a quarter century later, lead to the presidency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] First elected to Congress in 1936, Voorhis had defeated lackluster Republican opposition four times in the then-rural Los Angeles County district to win re-election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] For the 1946 election, Republicans sought a candidate who could unite the party and run a strong race against Voorhis in the Republican-leaning district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After failing to secure the candidacy of General George Patton, in November 1945 they settled on Lieutenant Commander Richard Nixon, who had lived in the district prior to his World War II service.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon spent most of 1946 campaigning in the district, while Voorhis did not return from Washington D.C. until the end of August.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon's campaign worked hard to generate publicity in the district, while Voorhis, dealing with congressional business in the capital, received little newspaper coverage.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis received the most votes in the June primary elections, but his percentage of the vote decreased from his share in the 1944 primaries.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] At five debates held across the district in September and October, Nixon was able to paint the incumbent as ineffectual and to suggest that Voorhis was connected to communist-linked organizations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis and his campaign were constantly on the defensive and were ineffective in rebutting Nixon's contentions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The challenger defeated Voorhis in the November general election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Various explanations have been put forward for Nixon's victory, from national political trends to red-baiting on the part of the challenger.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Some historians contend that Nixon received large amounts of funding from wealthy backers determined to defeat Voorhis, while others dismiss such allegations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] These matters remain subjects of historical debate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Since its creation following the 1930 census, the 12th district had been represented by Democrats.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The 12th stretched from just south of Pasadena to the Orange and San Bernardino county lines, encompassing such small towns as Whittier, Pomona and Covina.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The area has since been entirely absorbed into the Los Angeles megalopolis, but at the time it was principally agricultural.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The freeway system had barely touched the 12th district; only a small segment of the Pasadena Freeway cut across its northwest corner.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1932, John Hoeppel was elected to represent the 12th district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1936, Hoeppel was vulnerable as he had been convicted for trying to sell a nomination to West Point.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis defeated Hoeppel in the Democratic primary and easily won the general election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis, who gained a reputation as a respected and hard-working representative, nicknamed "Kid Atlas" by the press for taking the weight of the world on his shoulders, was loyal to the New Deal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The 12th district leaned Republican, the more so after 1941 when the Republican-dominated California State Legislature attempted to gerrymander Congressman Voorhis out of office by removing strong Democratic precincts in East Los Angeles from the district during the decennial redistricting.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The revamped 12th district had little industry and almost no union influence.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis was left with such Republican strongholds as San Marino, where he did not campaign, concluding that he would receive the same number of votes whether he visited there or not.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Despite the maneuvers of the Republicans in the legislature, Voorhis was re-elected in 1942, receiving 57% of the vote, and won with a similar percentage two years later.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis had not faced strong opposition prior to 1946.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In his initial election, Voorhis benefited from the Roosevelt landslide of 1936.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] His 1938 opponent was so shy that Voorhis had to introduce him to the crowd at a joint appearance.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1940, he faced Captain Irwin Minger, a little-known commandant of a military school, and his 1942 opponent, radio preacher and former Prohibition Party gubernatorial candidate Robert P.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1944, the 12th district Republicans were bitterly divided, and Voorhis easily triumphed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Voorhis served his fifth term in the House, Republicans searched for a candidate capable of defeating him.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Local Republicans formed what became known as the "Committee of One Hundred" (officially, the "Candidate and Fact-Finding Committee") to select a candidate with broad support in advance of the June 1946 primary election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Committee initially wooed State Commissioner of Education (and former Whittier College president) Walter Dexter.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Dexter was reluctant to give up his state post to run and sought a guarantee that he would receive another job if his candidacy failed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He continued to consider running for several months without reaching a decision, frustrating local Republicans.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Dexter dithered, Republicans tried to get General George Patton to run, though they were not certain if the general was a Republican.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, a day after the *Los Angeles Times* speculated on the run, Patton announced from Germany his intent to "keep completely out of politics".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Committee also contacted Stanley Barnes, a rising young Republican attorney and former football star at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Barnes declined to be considered, skeptical of the chances of defeating Voorhis.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] With little progress made on securing a high-profile candidate, Committee working groups held interviews.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Of the eight men who applied, the most prominent was former congressman John Hoeppel, who promised to keep "the Jews and the niggers" out of the district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On October 6, 1945, the Monrovia *News Post* reported that while Dexter seemed the likely candidate, "of course anything can happen in politics and generally does".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The *News Post* stated that other names discussed by the Committee included "Lt. [*sic*] Richard Nixon, U.S.N.R., of Whittier." Congressman Voorhis wrote to his father and political adviser, Charles Voorhis, on October 15, "I understand the General has decided not to run in the 12th district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Dexter would, in my opinion, be hard to beat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When Dexter finally turned the Committee down, he recommended Nixon, his onetime student.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Dexter died only days later of a heart attack, and Patton died in an auto accident before the 1946 campaign began.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] At the time, Nixon was stationed in Baltimore, Maryland, using his legal training to deal with military contract terminations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On November 1, 1945, he flew to California to meet influential Republicans and give a speech at a Committee meeting.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The meeting was advertised throughout the district and was open to any potential candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, the advertisements for the meeting noted that Nixon would be flying in to speak.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A number of potential rivals also showed up at the meeting on November 2, 1945, including a local judge and assemblyman.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon, who spoke last, was "electrifying", according to one Committee member.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When the Committee met to vote on November 28, Nixon received over two-thirds of the vote, which was then made unanimous.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Committee chairman Roy Day immediately notified the victor of the Committee's endorsement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was already arranging to research Voorhis's record and to meet with Republican leaders in Washington, including House Minority Leader (and future Speaker) Joseph W.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The newly minted candidate wrote to Day regarding Voorhis, "His 'conservative' reputation must be blasted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] But my main efforts are being directed toward building up a positive, progressive group of speeches which tell what we want to do, not what the Democrats have failed to do ...
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] I'm really hopped up over this deal, and I believe we can win." However, "wheelhorse" Republicans deemed Nixon's campaign hopeless.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was a virtual unknown outside of his hometown of Whittier and was facing a popular and respected incumbent.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Charles Voorhis wrote his son that the Republicans had endorsed a Quaker named Richard Nixon, but hoped that his son would retain a large part of the Quaker vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The elder Voorhis was confident that his son would triumph again, writing, "It is just another campaign that we have to go through ...
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was discharged from the Navy at the start of 1946.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Within days, he and his wife Pat Nixon, the latter almost eight months pregnant, returned to Whittier.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] They initially moved in with the candidate's parents, Frank and Hannah.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon returned to his old law firm, but spent most of his time campaigning.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Roy Day, chairman of the now-dissolved Committee, appointed himself as Nixon's campaign manager.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] This self-appointment dismayed the candidate somewhat, and Nixon unsuccessfully sought to replace Day.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis had been in Washington since August 1945, attending to congressional business.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He did not return to the district until August 1946, well after the June primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Beginning in February, the Republican hopeful began a heavy speaking schedule, addressing civic groups across the 400 square miles (1,000 km2) district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon's efforts to get publicity were aided by the birth of his daughter Tricia in late February.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The new father was extensively interviewed and photographed with his infant daughter.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Congressman Voorhis's office sent the Nixons a government pamphlet entitled *Infant Care*, of which representatives received 150 per month to distribute to their constituents.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When Richard Nixon sent his rival a note of thanks in early April, the congressman responded with a letter proposing that the two debate once Congress adjourned in August.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In mid-March, Nixon was approached by former congressman Hoeppel, who hated Voorhis.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Hoeppel offered to enter the Democratic primary in exchange for a payment of several hundred dollars plus the promise of a civil service job once the Republican was elected.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After consulting with his aides, Nixon turned him down.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Subsequently, Hoeppel filed as a Prohibition Party candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis was privy to these events through an informant close to the former representative, and was convinced that Roy Day had arranged to pay Hoeppel's filing fee.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The congressman feared that Hoeppel would serve as a stalking horse for Nixon, sparing the Republican from any "mudslinging".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis responded to Hoeppel's filing with a letter to his campaign manager, Baldwin Park realtor Jack Long, stating that "it would be worthwhile for us to try our level best to beat him in the Prohibition primary by a write-in campaign".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On March 18, two days before the filing deadline, Nixon filed in both the Republican and Democratic primaries under California's cross-filing system.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis also filed in the two major party primaries.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Under cross-filing, if the same candidate won both major party endorsements, he would be effectively elected, with only minor party candidates to stand against him.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Day advanced the $200 (the current equivalent of $2,230) for Nixon's filing fees, later noting that he had great difficulty being reimbursed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] By late March, Nixon's stock speeches to civic groups were becoming worn.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Day hired political consultant Murray Chotiner for $580 for the primary campaign, and the consultant warned that unless new life came into the campaign, it was in serious danger.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the following years, Chotiner was to become Nixon's campaign manager, adviser, and friend in an association that lasted until Chotiner's death a few months before President Nixon's 1974 resignation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Chotiner arranged for stories in local papers alleging that Voorhis had been endorsed by "the PAC", hoping that voters would take that to mean the Congress of Industrial Organizations's Political Action Committee (CIO-PAC).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The CIO was a labor federation which later merged with the American Federation of Labor to form the AFL-CIO.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] It had been organized in 1943 and took left-wing stands; its PAC was seen as a communist front organization by some.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A second PAC, the National Citizen's Political Action Committee (NCPAC) was also affiliated with the CIO, but was open to those outside the labor movement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Among the 1946 members of the NCPAC were actors Melvyn Douglas and Ronald Reagan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Both PACs had been headed by the late labor leader, Sidney Hillman, and the two organizations shared office space in New York City.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] While the CIO's national leadership decried communism; some of the local CIO-PAC branches were dominated by Communist Party members.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The CIO-PAC, which had endorsed Voorhis in 1944, refused to back him again.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Southern California chapter of the NCPAC endorsed Voorhis on April 1, 1946.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Chotiner's strategy was to conflate the two PACs in the public eye.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nourished by the PAC controversy, the Republican campaign gained new life as Nixon returned to the lecture circuit.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After Nixon spoke to a Lions Club meeting on May 1, a worried Voorhis supporter wrote to the congressman, "He carried the group by storm.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Both Voorhis and Nixon won his own party's primary, with Voorhis garnering a considerable number of votes in the Republican poll.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When all the votes from all primaries were added together, Voorhis outpolled Nixon by 7,000 votes.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's total percentage of the vote decreased from 60% in the 1944 primaries to 53.5% in 1946.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Hoeppel survived the write-in campaign to advance to the general election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Following a two-week vacation in British Columbia after the primary, Nixon returned to the 12th district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Republican began the general election campaign by replacing Roy Day with South Pasadena engineer Harrison McCall as campaign manager.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Chotiner was increasingly distracted by his position as Southern California campaign manager for the (successful) reelection bid of Republican Senator William Knowland, the Nixon campaign added publicist William Arnold.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis, on the other hand, remained in Washington, dealing with Congressional business and generating little publicity.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He corresponded with his father and with his campaign manager, Jack Long, by letter.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis hoped to return to California in mid-August but while returning from Washington in August, he was forced to have surgery for hemorrhoids in Ogden, Utah.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis spent two weeks in an Ogden hotel recuperating from the operation and did not return to the district until the end of August.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis wrote later, "I can't say I was exactly 'ready for the fray'.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon did not reply to Voorhis's April debate proposal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In May, the congressman wrote to Long as Nixon's campaign initially made the alleged PAC endorsement an issue.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis suggested that Nixon be challenged to debates as a matter of urgency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Long responded in June, saying that though Nixon was known as a champion debater during his Whittier College days, "with your age and experience the general public might not take kindly to your challenging a boy like Nixon".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Long advised awaiting a challenge from Nixon.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] By August, the two campaigns had settled on a debate to be held before a veteran's group in Whittier on September 20.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, the "Independent Voters of South Pasadena" (IVSP), headed by future Voorhis biographer Paul Bullock, announced a September 13 town meeting on campaign issues at South Pasadena Junior High School.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The IVSP's actual purpose in having the meeting was to get a vulnerable Republican assemblyman (who declined his invitation) to debate his Democratic rival, but Senate and 12th district Republican and Democratic candidates were invited.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Given that the debate sponsors were liberals, some of Nixon's aides advised him to refuse, but he overrode them.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Holifield of the neighboring 19th district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The town meeting attracted a packed crowd of over a thousand, with Nixon supporters distributing anti-Voorhis literature at the door.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Senate proxies spoke first for their candidates, followed by Voorhis.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon, who had notified organizers that he would be late due to another commitment, arrived during Voorhis's speech, and remained backstage until the congressman had completed his talk.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He then came onstage, shook hands with Voorhis, and delivered a fifteen-minute address.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A question-and-answer period then followed, with a Nixon supporter asking Voorhis about his onetime Socialist registration, and about his views on monetary policy.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After the representative responded, a Voorhis supporter asked Nixon why he was making "false charges" about the supposed Voorhis CIO-PAC endorsement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In response, Nixon reached into his pocket and pulled out a copy of a Southern California NCPAC bulletin mentioning the group's endorsement of Voorhis.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The congressman was unaware of the endorsement; those of his aides in the know had "completely forgotten" to tell him.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon walked halfway across the stage and displayed it to Voorhis, asking him to read it for himself.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis came from his seat and took it, and (according to Bullock, who served as timekeeper at the debate) "mumbled" that this seemed to be a different organization from the CIO-PAC.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the midst of the turmoil, Prohibition Party candidate Hoeppel came down the aisle (according to Bullock, possibly drunk) and demanded to know why he had been excluded from the debate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He was permitted to ask one question, of Voorhis, and the evening ended.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On September 19, Voorhis wired the NCPAC's Los Angeles and New York offices, requesting that "whatever qualified endorsement the Citizens PAC may have given me be withdrawn".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] By this time, newspapers across the district had printed Nixon's charges, along with a Nixon advertisement castigating Voorhis for allegedly accusing Nixon of lying about the PAC endorsement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Nixon biographer Roger Morris, the repudiation of NCPAC endorsements did not help Voorhis, as his actions "would seem to many a half-guilty shedding of sinister backing he never had.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The second debate was held at Patriotic Hall in Whittier on September 20.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As the debate was sponsored by the Whittier Ex-Servicemen's Association, attendance was limited to veterans.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The candidates debated the best way of dealing with the postwar housing shortage.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis favored restricting building of commercial structures to free up materials for housing, while Nixon urged the removal of all building restrictions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When Nixon repeated his PAC allegations, Voorhis noted his request to the NCPAC, stating that he could not be held responsible for its actions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Morris, the debate ended as a draw, or perhaps even a Voorhis victory.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Chotiner convinced Nixon that he needed to run an aggressive campaign to the end, and McCall challenged the Voorhis campaign to as many as eight additional debates, of which three were actually held.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The debates captured the interest of the public in the district and attracted large crowds.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The candidates were compared to Abraham Lincoln and Stephen Douglas, who had famously debated in their 1858 senatorial campaign, and bands played marches as each candidate entered the venue.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The two candidates' third meeting was held at Bridges Auditorium in Claremont on October 11.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis was, by his own admission, "awfully tired".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The candidates discussed labor policy, and Nixon "scored" by detailing a policy for dealing with public strikes that Voorhis too late realized was taken from a bill he had drafted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon took Voorhis aside after the debate and lambasted him for addressing him as "Lieutenant Commander Nixon", accusing him of pandering to former enlisted men's dislike of officers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the fourth debate, on October 23 at Monrovia High School, Nixon attacked Voorhis's congressional record.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The challenger alleged that in the previous four years, Voorhis only had been able to pass a single bill through Congress and into law.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The bill in question transferred jurisdiction over rabbit farming from the Department of the Interior to the Department of Agriculture.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon chided, "One has to be a rabbit to get effective representation in this congressional district." Voorhis responded that he had sponsored an act to employ the physically handicapped, but Nixon stated that it was not a law, but a joint resolution.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon restated his allegation regarding Voorhis and the PAC; Voorhis retorted that he had repudiated the NCPAC endorsement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon parried with a comment that Voorhis's voting record "earned him the endorsement, whether he wanted it or not".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon also contended that in 46 votes, Voorhis had almost entirely followed the CIO-PAC agenda.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Distraught, Voorhis stayed up until 4 am studying the votes Nixon had taxed him with.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He concluded that due to duplications, there were actually only 27 roll calls in question, on many of which he had opposed the CIO-PAC position.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The congressman also found that the votes "friendly" to the CIO-PAC included one authorizing a school lunch program.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The final debate took place October 28 at the San Gabriel Civic Auditorium, to an overflow crowd in excess of a thousand.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis went on the attack, charging Nixon with misrepresenting the "46 votes" to avoid real debate and any discussion of where Nixon himself stood on issues.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Republican candidate stated that he was fighting for "the person on a pension trying to keep up with the rising cost of living ... the white-collar worker who has not had a raise ...
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In mid October, the Nixon campaign unveiled an advertisement which foreshadowed his run for Senate four years later.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1950, a similar comparison between the voting record of Marcantonio and Democratic Senate nominee Douglas, printed on pink paper, came to be known as the "Pink Sheet".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Nixon campaign continued to run newspaper ads touching on the PAC issue.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] One ad suggested Radio Moscow had urged the election of the CIO slate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Others touched on Voorhis's past registration as a Socialist, and stated that his congressional record "is more Socialistic and Communistic than Democratic".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Democrats brought James Roosevelt and other prominent Democrats into the district to campaign for Voorhis.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon proposed that his wartime acquaintance, former Minnesota Governor Harold Stassen campaign for him.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, the candidate could not get permission from the California Republican committee for Stassen to visit.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis publicized a letter he had received from the Republican governor, Earl Warren, praising him for a disability insurance proposal he had made.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon supporters asked Warren for a letter praising Nixon, or at least a retraction of the Voorhis letter.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Warren refused, saying that Voorhis deserved the compliment, and Nixon would not receive an endorsement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] This conflict began a contentious relationship between Nixon and Warren which lasted until Warren's death shortly before Nixon's resignation as president.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] No polls had been taken during the campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On election night, Voorhis took an early lead in the vote count, but was soon overtaken by his challenger, whose margin increased as the night went on.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon defeated Voorhis by over 15,000 votes.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Republican won 19 of the 22 municipalities in the district, including Voorhis's home town of San Dimas.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis won the Democratic strongholds of El Monte and Monterey Park, as well as rural Baldwin Park.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] *Time* magazine's post-election issue came out in mid-November, and it praised the future president for "politely avoid[ing] personal attacks on his opponent".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Despite any hard feelings, Voorhis sent Nixon a letter of congratulations in early December 1946.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon and Voorhis met for an hour at Voorhis's office, and parted, according to Voorhis, as friends.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1971, Voorhis said that the two had never spoken again.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's final letter as a congressman, written on December 31, was to his father, who had been his political adviser throughout his congressional career.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Representative Voorhis wrote, "It has been primarily due to your help, your confidence, your advice ... above all to a feeling I have always had that your hand was on my shoulder.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis never ran again for political office, working as an executive in the cooperative movement for twenty years after his defeat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Hoeppel continued as publisher and editor of *National Defense* magazine, a publication for veterans, until his 1960 retirement, and died in Arcadia in 1976 at age 95.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon served two terms in the House, and in 1950 was elected to the United States Senate, continuing his political rise, which would lead him to the White House in 1969.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The 12th district race of 1946 was little noticed at the time.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Nixon became prominent, the 1946 race was scrutinized more closely.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon's defeat of Voorhis has been cited as the first of a number of red-baiting campaigns by the future president which elevated him to the House, the Senate, the Vice Presidency, and eventually put him in position to run for president.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon, in his 1978 memoir, stated that the central issue in the 1946 campaign was "the quality of life in postwar America", and he won because voters "had 'had enough,' and they decided to do something about it".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis, in his 1947 memoir, indicated that the "most important single factor in the campaign of 1946 was the difference in general attitude between the 'outs' and the 'ins'.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In later years, Voorhis had more to say about the reasons for his defeat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1958, he alleged that voters had received anonymous phone calls saying that he was a communist, that newspapers had stated that he was a fellow traveler, and that when Nixon got angry, he would "do anything".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In November 1962, after Nixon's defeat in the California gubernatorial race, Voorhis appeared on Howard K.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Smith's *News and Comment* program on ABC in the episode entitled "The Political Obituary of Richard M.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon" and complained about the way Nixon had conducted himself in the 1946 race.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's appearance was overshadowed by the controversial participation of Nixon adversary Alger Hiss.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1972, Voorhis authored a book, *The Strange Case of Richard Milhous Nixon*, in which he stated that Nixon was "quite a ruthless opponent" whose "one cardinal and unbreakable rule of conduct" was "to win, whatever it takes to do it".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1981, three years before his death, Voorhis denied in an interview that he had been endorsed by the NCPAC.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In an early draft of his memoir, Voorhis wrote that he had documentation showing that "the Nixon campaign was a creature of big eastern financial interests".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon biographer Irwin Gellman, writing in 1999, nine years after Morris, disagreed with the latter's conclusions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Gellman argued that the Committee was a "grassroots" group which was "far from sophisticated" in its efforts to find a candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Parmet wrote that the campaign was not well financed, "Nixon had to learn that money would be scarce until he became a winner ...
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Nixon campaign of 1946 *did* look like a shoestring affair." Aitken points out that Nixon spent no money on radio advertising during the campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Other allegations center on Murray Chotiner, painting him as the "evil genius" of the campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Part of this inflation is due to Chotiner himself, who, in later years, lost no opportunity to exaggerate his role in the 1946 race, to the annoyance of Day and McCall.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Nixon biographer Stephen Ambrose, "Nevertheless, the legend grew.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the eyes of Nixon's critics, as a candidate he was merely a front man for Chotiner's evil manipulations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A number of biographies on Nixon or Voorhis, or which otherwise touch on the 1946 campaign, state with varying degrees of certainty that during the final weekend of the campaign, anonymous calls were made to district households.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The caller would ask "Did you know Jerry Voorhis is a communist?" and then hang up.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Bullock, there was a phone bank staffed by workers who had responded to a newspaper ad, run by the Nixon organization in Alhambra.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Bullock cites as his source for this Zita Remley, a "Voorhis admirer", who stated that her niece had worked there.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Although the niece died before Bullock's book was written, according to Bullock, Remley's "reputation for veracity is unchallengeable".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon spent most of 1946 campaigning in the district, and worked hard to extend his name recognition beyond his hometown of Whittier.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Starting in the primary, the Nixon campaign made determined efforts to woo the district's newspapers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The campaign targeted smaller papers, especially the small weekly newspapers that were distributed for free; Republican surveys found that these were widely read and trusted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon supporter and Republican National Committeeman from California McIntyre Faries arranged to buy ads on behalf of the Nixon campaign on condition that the newspaper run an editorial at its direction (most of the papers were, in any event, Republican in their outlook).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] These efforts paid off; 26 of the 30 newspapers serving the district endorsed Nixon.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Nixon biographer Morris, Voorhis was given no coverage in newspapers, or limited to small paid advertisements.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The paper owners told the Voorhis campaign that, with the postwar paper shortage, space had to be saved for regular customers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's campaign, described by Bullock as "traditionally amateurish and poorly put together", was slow to perceive the threat presented by Nixon and remained continually on the defensive.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1971, in an article marking the 25th anniversary of the campaign, Voorhis acknowledged that "I never had much of an organization; frankly, there was no form to it.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] And we needed it badly in 1946." In the same article, the *Los Angeles Times* described Voorhis's campaign as "undermanned, underfinanced, outgunned, outmaneuvered and he apparently was on the wrong side of most of the issues of the day".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] His one avenue of outreach in the press was his newspaper column, *People's Business*, which ran in most local newspapers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In July 1946, Voorhis chose to suspend this column lest it be thought that he was using it as a means of campaigning.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Gellman, this weakened Voorhis's political outreach.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] One blunder identified by Gellman was Voorhis's decision to debate Nixon, as it raised the challenger's profile to the same level as the incumbent's.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] This decision was described by Morris as "quiet hubris".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Rather than return to campaign in the primary when he recognized Nixon's attractiveness, he remained in the capital, allowing Nixon to court newspaper publishers and reporters as well as constituents who wanted to have firsthand contact with their congressional representative.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] An election for a seat in the United States House of Representatives took place in California's 12th congressional district on November 2, 1948, the date set by law for the elections for the 81st United States Congress.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the 12th district election, the candidates were one-term incumbent Republican Richard Nixon, and Progressive challenger Una W.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was reelected with 87% of the vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In June, Nixon won the Republican primary uncontested, as well as the Democratic primary, defeating attorney Stephen I.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon would have gone on to the general election without an opponent, but because no members of the Independent Progressive Party ran in the primary, the party was later able to select Rosemead housewife Una W.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Rice boasted endorsements from the Pomona AFL Central labor Council, the Los Angeles CIO-PAC, and the California State Brotherhood of Locomotive Firemen and Enginemen.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] For his part, Nixon was so sure of his victory that he took time out of his own campaign to go on a nationwide speaking tour for Republican Presidential candidate Thomas E.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon spent election night with his family at the Ambassador Hotel's Cocoanut Grove, where he was invited onstage by singer Hildegarde.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He was ultimately reelected in a landslide.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The **1950 United States Senate election in California** was held on November 7 of that year, following a campaign characterized by accusations and name-calling.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Republican Representative and future President Richard Nixon defeated Democrat Representative Helen Gahagan Douglas, after Democratic incumbent Sheridan Downey withdrew during the primary election campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas and Nixon each gave up their congressional seats to run against Downey; no other representatives were willing to risk the contest.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Both Douglas and Nixon announced their candidacies in late 1949.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In March 1950, Downey withdrew from a vicious primary battle with Douglas by announcing his retirement, after which Los Angeles *Daily News* publisher Manchester Boddy joined the race.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy attacked Douglas as a leftist and was the first to compare her to New York Representative Vito Marcantonio, who was accused of being a communist.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy, Nixon, and Douglas each entered both party primaries, a practice known as cross-filing.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In the Republican primary, Nixon was challenged only by cross-filers and fringe candidates.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon won the Republican primary and Douglas the Democratic contest, with each also finishing third in the other party's contest (Boddy finished second in both races).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The contentious Democratic race left the party divided, and Democrats were slow to rally to Douglas—some even endorsed Nixon.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The Korean War broke out only days after the primaries, and both Nixon and Douglas contended that the other had often voted with Marcantonio to the detriment of national security.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon's attacks were far more effective, and he won the November 7 general election by almost 20 percentage points, carrying 53 of California's 58 counties and all metropolitan areas.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Though Nixon was later criticized for his tactics in the campaign, he defended his actions, and also stated that Douglas's positions were too far to the left for California voters.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Other reasons for the result have been suggested, ranging from tepid support for Douglas from President Harry S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Truman and his administration to the reluctance of voters in 1950 to elect a woman.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The campaign gave rise to two political nicknames, both coined by Boddy or making their first appearance in his newspaper: "the Pink Lady" for Douglas and "Tricky Dick" for Nixon.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] California Senator Sheridan Downey was first elected in 1938.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] An attorney, he had run unsuccessfully in 1934 for Lieutenant Governor of California as Upton Sinclair's running mate, and had a reputation as a liberal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] As a senator, however, his positions gradually moved to the right, and he began to favor corporate interests.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Manchester Boddy, the editor and publisher of the Los Angeles *Daily News*, was born on a potato farm in Washington state.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He had little newspaper experience when, in 1926, he was given the opportunity to purchase the *Daily News* by a bankruptcy court, but built it into a small but thriving periodical.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He shared his views with his readers through his column, "Thinking and Living", and, after initial Republican leanings, was a firm supporter of the New Deal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] While the *Daily News* had not endorsed the Sinclair–Downey ticket, Boddy had called Sinclair "a great man" and allowed the writer-turned-gubernatorial candidate to set forth his views on the newspaper's front page.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Both Helen Douglas and Richard Nixon entered electoral politics in the mid-1940s.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas, a New Deal Democrat, was a former actress and opera singer, and the wife of actor Melvyn Douglas.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She represented the 14th congressional district beginning in 1945.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon grew up in a working-class family in Whittier.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1946, he defeated 12th district Representative Jerry Voorhis to claim a seat in the United States House of Representatives in January 1947, where he became known for his anticommunist activities, including his involvement in the Alger Hiss affair.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In the 1940s, California experienced a huge influx of migrants from other US states, increasing its population by 55%.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Party registration in 1950 was 58.4% Democratic and 37.1% Republican.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, other than Downey, most major California officeholders were Republican, including Governor Earl Warren (who was seeking a third term in 1950) and Senator William Knowland.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] During the 1950 campaign, both Nixon and Douglas were accused of having a voting record comparable to that of New York Representative Vito Marcantonio.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The sole representative from the American Labor Party at the time, Marcantonio represented East Harlem.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He was accused of being a communist, though he denied being one; he rarely discussed the Soviet Union or communism.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Marcantonio opposed restrictions on communists and the Communist Party, stating that such restrictions violated the Bill of Rights.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He regularly voted against contempt citations requested by the House Un-American Activities Committee (HUAC), on which Nixon served.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas disregarded advice from party officials to wait until 1952 to run for the Senate, when Republican Senator Knowland would be up for reelection.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Fundraising for the campaign was a concern from the beginning; Douglas friend and aide Ed Lybeck wrote her that she would probably need to raise $150,000 ($1.8 million today), which Douglas considered a massive sum.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On October 5, 1949, Douglas made a radio appearance announcing her candidacy.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She attacked Downey almost continuously throughout the remainder of the year, accusing him of being a do-nothing, a tool of big business, and an agent of oil interests.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She hired Harold Tipton, a newcomer to California who had managed a successful congressional campaign in the Seattle area, as her campaign manager.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas realized that Nixon would most likely be the Republican nominee, and felt that were she to win the primary, the wide gap between Nixon's positions and hers would cause voters to rally to her.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey, who suffered from a severe ulcer, was initially undecided about running, but announced his candidacy in early December in a speech that included an attack on Douglas.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Earl Desmond, a member of the California State Senate from Sacramento whose positions were similar to Downey's, also entered the race.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In January 1950, Douglas opened campaign headquarters in Los Angeles and San Francisco, which was seen as a signal that she was serious about contesting Downey's seat and would not withdraw from the race.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey challenged Douglas to a series of debates; Douglas, who was not a good debater, declined.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The two candidates traded charges via press and radio, with Downey describing Douglas's views as extremist.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's formal campaign launch on February 28 was overshadowed by rumors that Downey might retire, which Douglas called a political maneuver on Downey's part to get the attention of the press.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, on March 29, amid rumors that he was doing badly in the polls, Downey announced both his retirement and his endorsement of Los Angeles *Daily News* publisher Manchester Boddy.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In his statement, the senator indicated that, due to his ill health, he was not up to "waging a personal and militant campaign against the vicious and unethical propaganda" of Douglas.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy filed his election paperwork the next day, on the final day petitions were accepted, with his papers signed by Los Angeles Mayor Fletcher Bowron, a Republican, and by Downey campaign manager and 1946 Democratic senatorial candidate Will Rogers Jr.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The publisher had been urged to enter the race by state Democratic leaders and by wealthy oilmen.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He had no political experience; Democratic leaders had sought to draft him to run for the Senate in 1946, but he had declined.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He later stated that his reasons for running were that the race would be a challenge, and that he would meet interesting people.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy, Douglas, and Nixon each "cross-filed", entering both major party primaries.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas called Downey's departure in favor of the publisher a cheap gimmick and made no attempt to reach a *rapprochement* with the senator, who entered Bethesda Naval Hospital for treatment in early April, and was on sick leave from Congress for several months.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The change in opponents was a mixed blessing for Douglas; it removed the incumbent from the field, but deprived her of the endorsement of the *Daily News*—one of the few big city papers to consistently support her.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] For the first month of Boddy's abbreviated ten-week campaign, he and Douglas avoided attacking each other.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy's campaign depicted him as born in a log cabin, and highlighted his World War I service.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The publisher campaigned under the slogan, "Manchester Boddy, the Democrat Every Body Wants." Boddy stated that he was fighting for the "little man", and alleged that the average individual was overlooked by both big government and big labor.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, his campaign, having a late start, was disorganized.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The candidate himself had little charisma, and little presence as a public speaker.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to Rob Wagner, who wrote of the campaign in his history of Los Angeles newspapers of the era, Boddy "was all sizzle and no substance".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The campaign calm broke off near the end of April 1950, when Boddy's *Daily News* and affiliated newspapers referred to the congresswoman as "decidedly pink" and "pink shading to deep red".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] At the end of the month, the *Daily News* referred to her for the first time as "the pink lady".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas generally ignored Boddy's attacks, which continued unabated through May.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In a *Daily News* column, Boddy wrote that Douglas was part of "a small minority of red hots" which proposed to use the election to "establish a beachhead on which to launch a Communist attack on the United States".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] One Boddy campaign publication was printed with red ink, and stated that Douglas "has too often teamed up with the notorious extreme radical, Vito Marcantonio of New York City, on votes that seem more in the interest of Soviet Russia than of the United States".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On May 3, Representative George Smathers defeated liberal Senator Claude Pepper for the Democratic Senate nomination in Florida.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Smathers' tactics included dubbing his opponent "Red Pepper" and distributing red-covered brochures, *The Red Record of Senator Claude Pepper*, that included a photograph of Pepper with Marcantonio.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Soon after Smathers' triumph in the primary, which in the days of the yellow dog South was tantamount to election, South Dakota Republican Senator Karl Mundt, who when in the House had served with Nixon on HUAC, sent him a letter telling him about Smathers' brochure.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey reentered the fray on May 22, when he made a statewide radio address on behalf of Boddy, stating his belief that Douglas was not qualified to be a senator.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He concluded, "Her record clearly shows very little hard work, no important influence on legislation, and almost nothing in the way of solid achievement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas brought an innovation to the race—a small helicopter, which she used to travel around the state at a time when there were few freeways linking California's cities.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She got the idea from her friend, Texas Senator and future President Lyndon Johnson, who had extensively used helicopters in his campaign during the heavily contested Democratic Party primary for the 1948 United States Senate election in Texas.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas leased the craft from a helicopter company in Palo Alto owned by Republican supporters, who hoped her influence would lead to a defense contract.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When she used it to land in San Rafael, her local organizer, Dick Tuck, called it the "Helencopter", and the name stuck.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In early April, polls gave Nixon some chance of winning the Democratic primary, which would mean his election was secured.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He sent out mailings to Democratic voters.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy attacked Nixon for the mailings; Nixon responded that Democratic voters should have the opportunity to express no confidence in the Truman administration by voting for a Republican.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] "Democrats for Nixon", a group affiliated with Nixon's campaign, asked Democratic voters "as one Democrat to another" to vote for the congressman, sending out flyers which did not mention his political affiliation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy quickly struck back in his paper, accusing Nixon of misrepresenting himself as a Democrat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A large ad in the same issue by the "Veterans Democratic Committee" warned Democratic voters that Nixon was actually a Republican and referred to him for the first time as "Tricky Dick".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The exchange benefited neither Nixon nor Boddy; Douglas won the primary on June 6 and exceeded their combined vote total.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In mid-1949, Nixon, although anxious to advance his political career, was reluctant to run for the Senate unless he was confident of winning the Republican primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He considered his party's prospects in the House to be bleak, absent a strong Republican trend, and wrote "I seriously doubt if we can ever work our way back in power.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In late August 1949, Nixon embarked on a putatively nonpolitical speaking tour of Northern California, where he was less well known, to see if his candidacy would be well received if he ran.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With many of his closest advisers urging him to do so, Nixon decided in early October to seek the Senate seat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He hired a professional campaign manager, Murray Chotiner, who had helped to run successful campaigns for both Governor Warren and Senator Knowland and had played a limited role in Nixon's first congressional race.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon announced his candidacy in a radio broadcast on November 3, painting the race as a choice between a free society and state socialism.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner's philosophy for the primary campaign was to focus on Nixon and ignore the opposition.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon did not indulge in negative campaigning in the primaries; according to Nixon biographer Irwin Gellman, the internecine warfare in the Democratic Party made it unnecessary.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The Nixon campaign spent most of late 1949 and early 1950 concentrating on building a statewide organization, and on intensive fundraising, which proved successful.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon had built part of his reputation in the House on his role in the Alger Hiss affair.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Hiss's retrial for perjury after a July 1949 hung jury was a cloud over Nixon's campaign; if Hiss was acquitted, Nixon's candidacy would be in serious danger.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On January 21, 1950, the jury found Hiss guilty, and Nixon received hundreds of congratulatory messages, including one from the only living former president, Herbert Hoover.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Houser eventually decided against running.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Los Angeles County Supervisor Raymond Darby commenced a Senate run, but changed his mind and instead ran for lieutenant governor.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Darby was defeated by incumbent Lieutenant Governor Goodwin Knight in the Republican primary.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Knight had also been considered likely to run for the Senate, but decided to seek re-election instead.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Actor Edward Arnold began a Senate run, but dropped it in late March, citing a lack of time to prepare his campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On March 20, Nixon cross-filed in the two major party primaries, and two weeks later began to criss-cross the state in his campaign vehicle: a yellow station wagon with "Nixon for U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to one contemporary news account, in his "barnstorming tour", Nixon intended to "[talk] up his campaign for the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Senate on street corners and wherever he can collect a crowd." During his nine-week primary tour, he visited all of California's 58 counties, speaking sometimes six or eight times in a day.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] His wife Pat Nixon stood by as her husband spoke, distributing campaign thimbles that urged the election of Nixon and were marked with the slogan "Safeguard the American Home".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She distributed more than 65,000 by the end of the campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With no serious challenge from Republican opponents, Nixon won an overwhelming victory in the Republican primary, with his cross-filing rivals, Boddy, Douglas, and Desmond, dividing a small percentage of the vote but running well ahead of the two fringe candidates.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] There were no candidate debates, but Douglas and Nixon met twice on the campaign trail during the primary season.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The first meeting took place at the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco, where Nixon waved a check for $100 that his campaign had received from "Eleanor Roosevelt", with an accompanying letter, "I wish it could be ten times more.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Best wishes for your success." The audience was shocked at the idea of Eleanor Roosevelt, widow of Democratic former president Franklin Roosevelt and known for her liberal views, contributing to Nixon's campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon went on to explain that the envelope was postmarked Oyster Bay, New York, and that the Eleanor Roosevelt who had sent the contribution was Eleanor Butler Roosevelt, the widow of former Republican president Theodore Roosevelt's eldest son.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The audience laughed, and Douglas later wrote that she had been distracted and gave a poor speech.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A memo from Chotiner several days later noted that Boddy had failed to attend the function, and that Douglas wished that she had also not attended.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A second joint appearance took place in Beverly Hills.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to Nixon campaign adviser Bill Arnold, Douglas arrived late, while Nixon was already speaking.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon ostentatiously looked at his watch, provoking laughter from the audience.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The laughter recurred as Nixon, sitting behind Douglas as she spoke, fidgeted to indicate his disapproval of what she was saying; she appeared bewildered at the laughter.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas concluded her remarks and Nixon rose to speak again, but she did not stay to listen.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The rift in the Democratic party caused by the primary was slow to heal; Boddy's supporters were reluctant to join Douglas's campaign, even with President Truman's encouragement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The President refused to campaign in California; he resented Democratic gubernatorial candidate James Roosevelt.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Roosevelt, the eldest son of Franklin Roosevelt, had urged Democrats not to nominate Truman in 1948, but to instead choose General Dwight Eisenhower.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Fundraising continued to be a major problem for Douglas, the bulk of whose financial support came from labor unions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The weekend after the primary, Nixon campaign officials held a conference to discuss strategy for the general election campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] They decided on a fundraising goal of just over $197,000 (today, about $2,400,000).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] They were helped in that effort when Democratic Massachusetts Congressman John F.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Kennedy, a political opponent of Nixon's, came to Nixon's office and gave him a donation of $1,000 on behalf of Joseph P.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] John Kennedy indicated that he could not endorse Nixon, but that he would not be heartbroken if Douglas was returned to her acting career.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Joseph Kennedy later stated that he gave Nixon the money because Douglas was a communist.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon's positions generally favored large corporations and farming interests, while Douglas's did not, and Nixon reaped the reward with contributions from them.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon favored the Taft–Hartley Act, passage of which had been bitterly opposed by labor unions; Douglas advocated its repeal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas supported a requirement that federally subsidized water from reclamation projects only go to farms of not more than 160 acres (0.65 km2); Nixon fought for the repeal of that requirement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When the Korean War broke out in late June, Douglas and her aides feared being put on the defensive by Nixon on the subject of communism, and sought to preempt his attack.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's opening campaign speech included a charge that Nixon had voted with Marcantonio to deny aid to South Korea and to cut aid to Europe in half.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon objected to Douglas's speech, stating that he had opposed the Korea bill because it did not include aid to Taiwan, and had supported it once the aid had been included.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] As for the Europe charge, according to Nixon biographer Stephen Ambrose, Nixon was so well known as a supporter of the Marshall Plan that Douglas's charge had no credibility.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In fact, Nixon had opposed a two-year reauthorization of the Marshall Plan, favoring a one-year reauthorization with a renewal provision, allowing for more congressional oversight.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon realized that the battle in California would be fought over the threat of communism, and his campaign staff began to research Douglas's voting record.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Republican officials in Washington sent the campaign a report listing 247 times Marcantonio (who generally followed the Democratic line) and Douglas had voted together, and 11 times that they had not.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Public support for the Korean War initially resulted in anger towards communists, and Nixon advocated the passage of legislation he had previously introduced with Senator Mundt which would tighten restrictions on communists and the Communist Party.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas argued that there was already sufficient legislation to effect any necessary prosecutions, and that the Mundt–Nixon bill (soon replaced by the similar McCarran–Wood bill) would erode civil liberties.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With the bill sure to pass, Douglas was urged to vote in favor to provide herself with political cover.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She declined to do so, though fellow California Representative Chester E.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Holifield warned her that she would not be able to get around the state fast enough to explain her vote and Nixon would "beat [her] brains in".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas was one of only 20 representatives (including Marcantonio) who voted against the bill.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Truman vetoed it; Congress enacted it over his veto by wide margins in late September.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas was one of 47 representatives (including Marcantonio) to vote to sustain the veto.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In a radio broadcast soon after the veto override, Douglas announced that she stood with the President, Attorney General J.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Edgar Hoover in their fight against communism.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On September 10, Eleanor Roosevelt, the late president's widow and the gubernatorial candidate's mother, arrived in California for a quick campaign swing to support her son and Douglas before she had to return to New York as a delegate to the United Nations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas hoped that the former first lady's visit would mark a turning point in the campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Roosevelt the next day in Long Beach, Nixon workers first handed out a flyer headed "Douglas–Marcantonio Voting Record", printed with dark ink on pink paper.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The legal-size flyer compared the voting records of Douglas and Marcantonio, principally in the area of national security, and concluded that they were indistinguishable.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In contrast, the flyer said, Nixon had voted entirely in opposition to the "Douglas–Marcantonio Axis".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] It implied that sending Douglas to the Senate would be no different from electing Marcantonio, and asked if that was what Californians wanted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The paper soon became known as the "Pink Sheet".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner later stated that the color choice was made at the print shop when campaign officials approved the final copy, and "for some reason or other it just seemed to appeal to us for the moment".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] An initial print run of 50,000 was soon followed by a reprint of 500,000, distributed principally in heavily populated Southern California.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas made no immediate response to the Pink Sheet, despite the advice of Mrs.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Roosevelt, who appreciated its power and urged her to answer it.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas later stated that she had failed to understand the appeal of the Pink Sheet to voters, and simply thought it absurd.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon followed up on the Pink Sheet with a radio address on September 18, accusing Douglas of being "a member of a small clique which joins the notorious communist party-liner Vito Marcantonio of New York, in voting time after time against measures that are for the security of this country".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He assailed Douglas for advocating that Taiwan's seat on the United Nations Security Council be given to the People's Republic of China, as appeasement towards communism.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Late in September, Douglas complained of alleged whispering campaigns aimed at her husband's Jewish heritage, and which stated that he was a communist.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] At the end of September, the splits in the Democratic Party became open when 64 prominent Democrats, led by George Creel, endorsed Nixon and castigated Douglas.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Creel said, "She has voted consistently with Vito Marcantonio.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Belated flag-waving cannot erase this damning record, nor can the tawdry pretense of 'liberalism' excuse it." According to Creel, Downey was working behind the scenes to secure Nixon's election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] James Roosevelt's lackluster campaign led Douglas backers to state that he was not only failing to help Douglas, he was not even helping himself.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With polls showing the two major Democratic candidates in dire straits, Roosevelt wrote to President Truman, proposing that Truman campaign in the state in the final days before the election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He also declined Douglas's pleas for a letter of support (privately calling her "one of the worst nuisances"), and even refused to allow her to be photographed with him at a signing ceremony for a water bill which would benefit California.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When Truman flew to Wake Island in early October to confer with General Douglas MacArthur regarding the Korean situation, he returned via San Francisco, but told the press he had no political appointments scheduled.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He spoke at an event at the War Memorial Opera House during his stopover, but both Roosevelt and Douglas were relegated to orchestra-level seats, far from the presidential box.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Vice President Alben Barkley did visit the state to campaign for the Democrats.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, *Time* magazine wrote that he did not appear to be helpful to Douglas's campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The Vice President stated that while he was not familiar with Douglas's votes, he was certain that she had voted the way she did out of sincere conviction and urged Californians to give the Senate a "dose of brains and beauty".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Attorney General McGrath also came to California to campaign for the Democrats, and freshman Senator Hubert Humphrey of Minnesota tirelessly worked the San Joaquin Valley, talking to farmers and workers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas adopted Boddy's "Tricky Dick" nickname for Nixon, and also referred to him as "pee wee".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Her name-calling had an effect on Nixon: when told she had called him "a young man with a dark shirt" in an allusion to Nazism, he inquired, "Did she say that?
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Why, I'll castrate her." Campaign official Bill Arnold joked that it would be difficult to do, and Nixon replied that he would do it anyway.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon returned the attacks; at friendly gatherings and especially at all-male events, he stated that Douglas was "pink right down to her underwear".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's last large-scale advertisement blitz contained another Nazi allusion.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Citing five votes in which Nixon and Marcantonio had voted together and in opposition to Douglas, it accused Nixon of using "the big lie" and stated: "HITLER invented it/STALIN perfected it/NIXON uses it".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The iron curtain of silence has closed around the opposition camp." Through the final days of the campaign, he struck a constant drumbeat: Douglas was soft on communism.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Though polls showed Nixon well ahead, his campaign did not let up.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A fundraising solicitation warned, "Right Now Nixon Is Losing ...
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Skywriting urged voters to cast their ballots for him.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Borrowing an idea from Nixon's 1946 campaign, the campaign announced that people should answer their phones, "Vote for Nixon"; random calls would be made from campaign headquarters and households that answered their phones that way would receive scarce consumer appliances.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner even instructed that 18-month-old copies of *The Saturday Evening Post*, containing a flattering story about Nixon, be left in doctor's offices, barber shops, and other places where people wait across the state.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In the last days of the campaign, Douglas finally began to receive some of the support she had hoped for.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy's paper endorsed her, while Truman praised her.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's actor husband, Melvyn Douglas, on tour with the play *Two Blind Mice* throughout the campaign, spoke out on behalf of his wife, as did movie stars Myrna Loy and Eddie Cantor.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon had several Hollywood personalities supporting him, including Howard Hughes, Cecil B.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Another actor, Ronald Reagan, was among Douglas's supporters, but when his girlfriend and future wife Nancy Davis took him to a pro-Nixon rally led by actress ZaSu Pitts, he was converted to Nixon's cause and led quiet fundraising for him.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas was apparently unaware of this—30 years later she mentioned Reagan in her memoirs as someone who worked hard for her.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner had worked on Warren's 1942 campaign, but had parted ways from him, and the popular governor did not want to be connected to the Nixon campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nonetheless, Chotiner sought to maneuver him into an endorsement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner instructed Young Republicans head and future congressman Joseph F.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Holt to follow Douglas from appearance to appearance and demand to know who she was supporting for governor, as other Young Republicans handed out copies of the Pink Sheet.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas repeatedly avoided the question, but with four days to go before the election and the Democratic candidate near exhaustion from the bitter campaign, she responded that she hoped and prayed that Roosevelt would be elected.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Despite the polls, Douglas was confident that the Democratic registration edge would lead her to victory, so much so that she offered a Roosevelt staffer a job in her senatorial office.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On election day, November 7, 1950, Nixon defeated Douglas by 59 percent to 41.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Of California's 58 counties, Douglas won only five, all in Northern California and with relatively small populations; Nixon won every urban area.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Although Warren defeated Roosevelt by an even larger margin, Nixon won by the greatest number of votes of any 1950 Senate candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas, in her concession speech, declined to congratulate Nixon.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Marcantonio was also defeated in his New York district.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A week after the election, Downey announced that he was resigning for health reasons.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Warren appointed Nixon to the short remainder of Downey's term; under the Senate rules at the time, this gave Nixon seniority over the new senators sworn in during January 1951.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon took office on December 4, 1950, after resigning from the House.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He used little of his seniority, since in November 1952 he was elected vice president as Dwight Eisenhower's running mate, the next step on a path that would lead him to the presidency in 1969.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey, who as a former senator retained floor privileges, was hired as a lobbyist by oil interests.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1952, as Republicans took over the White House and control of both houses of Congress, he was fired.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] An aide stated that the big corporations did not need Downey anymore.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy, dispirited by his election defeat and feeling let down by the average citizens for whom he had sought to advocate, lapsed into semi-retirement after his primary defeat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1952, he sold his interest in the *Daily News*, which went into bankruptcy in December 1954.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] It was rumored that Douglas would be given a political appointment in the Truman administration, but the Nixon–Douglas race had made such an appointment too controversial for the President.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to Democratic National Committee vice-chair India Edwards, a Douglas supporter, the former congresswoman could not have been appointed dogcatcher.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1952, she returned to acting, and eight years later campaigned for John F.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Kennedy during Nixon's first, unsuccessful presidential run.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She also campaigned for George McGovern in his unsuccessful bid to prevent Nixon's 1972 reelection, and called for his ouster from office during the Watergate scandal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Less than a week after the election, Douglas wrote to one of her supporters that she did not think there was anything her campaign could have done to change the result.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Blaming the war, voter mistrust of Truman's foreign policy, and high prices at home, Douglas stated that she lost in California because Nixon was able to take a large part of the women's vote and the labor vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Later in November, she indicated that liberals must undertake a massive effort to win in 1952.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1956, she stated in an interview that, while Nixon had never called her a communist, he had designed his whole campaign to create the impression that she was a communist or "communistic".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1959, she wrote that she had not particularly wanted to be a senator, and in 1962 she stated that the policy of her campaign was to avoid attacks on Nixon.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In her memoirs, published posthumously in 1982, she wrote, "Nixon had his victory, but I had mine ...
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1958, Nixon, by then vice president, allegedly stated that he regretted some of the tactics his campaign had used in the campaign against Douglas, blaming his youth.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When the statements were reported, Nixon denied them.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He issued press releases defending his campaign, and stating that any impression that Douglas was pro-communist was justified by her record.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He said Douglas was part of a whispering campaign accusing him of being "anti-Semitic and Jim Crow".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Contemporary accounts ascribed the result to a number of causes.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas friend and former Interior Secretary Harold L.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Ickes blamed Roosevelt's weak candidacy and what he believed was Nixon's use of the red scare.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Supervisor John Anson Ford of Los Angeles County chalked up the result to Nixon's skill as a speaker and a lack of objective reporting by the press.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's campaign treasurer, Alvin Meyers, stated that while labor financed Douglas's campaign, it failed to vote for her, and blamed the Truman Administration for "dumping" her.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's San Diego campaign manager claimed that 500,000 people in San Diego and Los Angeles had received anonymous phone calls alleging Douglas was a communist, though he could not name anyone who had received such a call.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] *Time* magazine wrote that Nixon triumphed "by making the Administration's failures in Asia his major issue".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] As Nixon continued his political rise and then moved towards his downfall, the 1950 race increasingly took on sinister tones.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Historian Ingrid Scobie came to a different conclusion in her biography of Douglas, *Center Stage*.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Scobie concluded that, given voter attitudes at the time, no woman could have won that race.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In his early biography of Nixon, Mazo contrasted the two campaigns and concluded, "when compared with the surgeons of the Nixon camp, the Douglas operators performed like apprentice butchers".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Both Roger Morris and Greg Mitchell (who wrote a book about the 1950 race) conclude that Nixon spent large sums of money on the campaign, with Morris estimating $1–2 million (perhaps $12 million–$24 million today) and Mitchell suggesting twice that.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Gellman, in his later book, conceded that Nixon's officially reported amount of $4,209 was understated, but indicated that campaign finance law at that time was filled with loopholes, and few if any candidates admitted to their full spending.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He considered Morris's and Mitchell's earlier estimates, though, to be "guess[es]" and "fantastic".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Black suggests that Nixon spent about $1.5 million and Douglas just under half of that.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The **1952 Republican National Convention** was held at the International Amphitheatre in Chicago, Illinois from July 7 to 11, 1952, and nominated Dwight D.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower of New York, nicknamed "Ike", for president and then Richard M.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The 1952 Republican convention was the first political convention to be televised live, coast-to-coast.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Experiments in regionally broadcasting conventions took place during the Republican and Democratic conventions in 1948; however, 1952 was the first year in which networks carried nationwide coverage of political conventions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Fixed cameras were placed at the back and the sides of the International Amphitheatre for the press to use collectively.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] None of these offered a straight shot of the podium on stage, so many networks supplemented their coverage with shots from their own portable cameras.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The keynote speech was delivered by MacArthur, who had become a hero to Republicans after President Truman relieved him of command in 1951 because of their disagreement about how to prosecute the Korean War, and had hopes of obtaining the presidential nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] In his address, MacArthur condemned the Truman administration for America's perceived loss of status on the international stage, including criticism of the Yalta Conference and the administration's handling of the war in Korea.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] MacArthur also criticized Truman on the domestic front, blaming his administration for wages that failed to keep pace with post-World War II inflation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The speech was not well received, and did nothing to aid MacArthur's presidential campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] He curtailed his post-convention speeches and remained out of the public eye until after the election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The contest for the presidential nomination was expected to be a battle between the party's moderate-to-liberal and conservative wings.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Moderate and liberal Republicans (the "Eastern Establishment"), led by New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey, the party's unsuccessful presidential nominee in 1944 and 1948, were largely supporters of Eisenhower or Warren.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The conservative wing was led by Robert A.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Taft, who had unsuccessfully tried for the presidential nomination in 1940 and 1948.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The Taft-dominated Republican National Committee supported Taft in the dispute.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] When delegate committees met to consider the issue before the convention convened, they sustained Eisenhower's position.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Stripped of 42 delegates from the disputed states, Taft's backers realized their chances of beating Eisenhower were slim.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] In his remarks during the delegate fight, Taft supporter Everett Dirksen harshly criticized Dewey and the moderate-to-liberal wing of the party, which had dominated it since 1940.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] McKeldin's nomination was seconded by Kansas Governor Edward F.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Arn, Oregon Republican Party Chairman Robert B.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Alberta Green, a delegate from West Plains, Missouri, and Hobson R.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Reynolds, an African American funeral director, state legislator from Philadelphia, and Director of the Civil Liberties Department of the Improved Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks of the World.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] After the nominations were completed, including speeches on behalf of Earl Warren, Harold Stassen, and Douglas MacArthur, the delegates proceeded to vote.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] After the first ballot, Eisenhower had 595 votes, nine short of the 604 required for the nomination, while Taft was a strong second with 500: Warren had 81, Stassen 20, and MacArthur 10.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Warren's backers refused to change their votes to Eisenhower because they still hoped for a deadlock that might enable Warren to obtain the nomination as a compromise choice.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Stassen had not received 10% of the vote, which freed his home state of Minnesota's delegates from their pledge to support him: all but one of the Stassen delegates, led by Warren E.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Burger, then changed their votes to Eisenhower, giving him 614 votes and securing him the presidential nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] After the revised totals were announced, Taft and Warren supporters moved to unanimously nominate Eisenhower, which the delegates did.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] As soon as Eisenhower was nominated, he visited Taft personally to request his endorsement and obtain a promise that Taft would support the Republican ticket.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Taft immediately agreed, and loyally backed Eisenhower during the general election campaign.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The nomination of Eisenhower in a single round of balloting marked the fifteenth time Republicans had selected their nominee on the first ballot.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] In the twenty-five national conventions the party had held since 1856, the party had averaged four ballots to select its presidential nominees.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon's speech at a state Republican Party fundraiser in New York City on May 8, 1952, impressed Governor Thomas E.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey, who was an Eisenhower supporter and had formed a pro-Eisenhower delegation from New York to attend the national convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] In a private meeting after the speech, Dewey suggested to Nixon that he would make a suitable vice presidential candidate on the ticket with Eisenhower.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon attended the convention as a delegate pledged to Earl Warren and represented California on the convention's platform committee.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] In pre-convention remarks to reporters, Nixon touted Warren as the most prominent dark horse and suggested that if Warren was not the presidential nominee, Nixon's Senate colleague William Knowland would be a good choice for vice president.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] As the convention proceedings continued, Warren became concerned that Nixon was working for Eisenhower while ostensibly pledged to Warren.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Davis of the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, who had been a vice president at Columbia University while Eisenhower was the school's president, to tell Eisenhower that Warren resented such actions and wanted them to stop.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower informed Davis that he did not oppose Warren, because if Taft and Eisenhower deadlocked, then Warren would be his first choice for the nomination.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] In the same conversation, Eisenhower indicated that if he won the nomination, Nixon would be his first choice for the vice presidency, because Eisenhower believed the party needed to promote leaders who were aggressive, capable, and young.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower later developed a list of seven potential candidates, with Nixon's name at the top.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] After Eisenhower was nominated, his key supporters met to discuss vice presidential possibilities.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower informed the group's chairman, Herbert Brownell Jr. that he did not wish to appear to dictate to the convention by formally sponsoring a single candidate, so the group reviewed several, including Taft, Everett Dirksen, and Alfred E.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Driscoll, all of whom they quickly rejected.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey then raised Nixon's name; the group quickly concurred.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Brownell checked with Eisenhower, who indicated his approval.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Brownell then called Nixon to inform him that he was Eisenhower's choice.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon accepted, then departed for Eisenhower's hotel room to discuss the details of the campaign and Eisenhower's plans for his vice president if the ticket was successful in the general election.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] A group of women delegates (led by former congresswoman Clare Boothe Luce) had hopes of putting forward a female vice presidential candidate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] This group sought to nominate Senator Margaret Chase Smith of Maine, but Smith requested that her name not be used.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Noting that Eisenhower's supporters had coalesced around Nixon, Luce withdrew her nomination of Smith.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] The delegates soon assembled to formalize the selection.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon asked Knowland to nominate him, and Knowland agreed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] Bricker declined Nixon's request to second the nomination, Driscoll agreed to do so.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/1952-republican-national-convention] There were no other candidates, and Nixon was nominated by acclamation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The **Endangered Species Act of 1973** (**ESA**; 16 U.S.C. § 1531 et seq.) is the primary law in the United States for protecting and conserving imperiled species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Designed to protect critically imperiled species from extinction as a "consequence of economic growth and development untempered by adequate concern and conservation", the ESA was signed into law by President Richard Nixon on December 28, 1973.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Supreme Court described it as "the most comprehensive legislation for the preservation of endangered species enacted by any nation".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The purposes of the ESA are two-fold: to prevent extinction and to recover species to the point where the law's protections are not needed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It therefore "protect[s] species and the ecosystems upon which they depend" through different mechanisms.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For example, section 4 requires the agencies overseeing the ESA to designate imperiled species as threatened or endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Section 9 prohibits unlawful 'take,' of such species, which means to "harass, harm, hunt..." Section 7 directs federal agencies to use their authorities to help conserve listed species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The ESA also serves as the enacting legislation to carry out the provisions outlined in The Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act is administered by two federal agencies, the United States Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) and the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] FWS and NMFS have been delegated by the Act with the authority to promulgate any rules and guidelines within the Code of Federal Regulations to implement its provisions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Calls for wildlife conservation in the United States increased in the early 1900s because of the visible decline of several species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] One example was the near-extinction of the bison, which used to number in the tens of millions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Similarly, the extinction of the passenger pigeon, which numbered in the billions, caused concern.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The whooping crane also received widespread attention as unregulated hunting and habitat loss contributed to a steady decline in its population.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] By 1890, it had disappeared from its primary breeding range in the north central United States.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Scientists of the day played a prominent role in raising public awareness about the losses.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For example, George Bird Grinnell highlighted bison decline by writing articles in *Forest and Stream*.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] To address these concerns, Congress enacted the Lacey Act of 1900.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Lacey Act was the first federal law that regulated commercial animal markets.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It also prohibited the sale of illegally killed animals between states (interstate commerce).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Other legislation followed, including the Migratory Bird Conservation Act, a 1937 treaty prohibiting the hunting of right and gray whales, and the Bald and Golden Eagle Protection Act of 1940.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Despite these treaties and protections, many populations still continued to decline.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] By 1941, only an estimated 16 whooping cranes remained in the wild.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] By 1963, the bald eagle, the national symbol of the U.S., was in danger of extinction in the lower 48 states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Only around 487 nesting pairs remained outside of Alaska.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Loss of habitat, shooting, and DDT poisoning contributed to its decline.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Fish and Wildlife Service tried to prevent the extinction of these species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Yet, it lacked the necessary Congressional authority and funding.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In response to this need, Congress passed the Endangered Species Preservation Act (Pub.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act initiated a program to conserve, protect, and restore select species of native fish and wildlife.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As a part of this program, Congress authorized the Secretary of the Interior to acquire land or interests in land that would further the conservation of these species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Department of Interior issued the first list of endangered species in March 1967.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It included 14 mammals, 36 birds, 6 reptiles, 6 amphibians, and 22 fish.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A few notable species listed in 1967 were the grizzly bear, American alligator, Florida manatee, and bald eagle.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Preservation Act was repealed by the Endangered Species Act of 1973.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Conservation Act of 1969 (Pub.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] 91–135) amended the Endangered Species Preservation Act of 1966.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It established a list of species in danger of worldwide extinction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It also expanded protections for species covered in 1966 and added to the list of protected species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] While the 1966 Act only applied to 'game' and wild birds, the 1969 Act also protected mollusks and crustaceans.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Punishments for poaching or unlawful importation or sale of these species were also increased.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Any violation could result in a $10,000 fine or up to one year of jail time.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Notably, the Act called for an international convention or treaty to conserve endangered species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A 1963 IUCN resolution called for a similar international convention.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In February 1973 a meeting in Washington, D.C. was convened.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] This meeting produced the comprehensive multilateral treaty known as CITES, or the Convention on International Trade of Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Conservation Act of 1969 provided a template for the Endangered Species Act of 1973 by using the term "based on the best scientific and commercial data." This standard is used as a guideline to determine if a species is in danger of extinction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In 1972, President Nixon declared current species conservation efforts to be inadequate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] He called on the 93rd United States Congress to pass comprehensive endangered species legislation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Congress responded with a completely rewritten law, the Endangered Species Act of 1973, which was signed by Nixon on December 28, 1973 (Pub.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It was written by a team of lawyers and scientists, including Russell E.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Train, the first appointed head of the Council on Environmental Quality (CEQ), an outgrowth of the National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA) of 1969.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Train was assisted by a core group of staffers, including Earl Baysinger at EPA, Dick Gutting, and Gerard A.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] "We didn't know what we couldn't do", Bertrand has said about the Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Significant amendments to the Act happened only four times during the first half-century of the Act's implementation: 1978, 1982, 1988, and 2004.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] These are listed and summarized on a U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Fish and Wildlife Service webpage titled, "History of the Endangered Species Act: Principal Amendments".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] How the official regulations for implementing the Act have developed and changed through time is more complex and is not available on the agency website.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Endangered Species Act is administered by two federal agencies, the United States Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) and the National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] NMFS handles most marine species, and the FWS has responsibility over freshwater fish and all other species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Species that occur in both habitats (e.g. sea turtles and Atlantic sturgeon) are jointly managed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The 1973 Act is considered a landmark conservation law.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Formal regulations published in the *Federal Register* that specify how the Act will be implemented have also changed through time.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In recent years, U.S. presidential elections that greatly shift environmental priorities have culminated in regulatory shifts in endangered species management back and forth.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Congressional elections also affect implementation of the Act via expansions or contractions in annual funding decisions for the agencies.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A distinction of the 1973 Act is that, unlike the previous legislation, plants became eligible for listing.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Fifty years later, significantly more species of plants were listed in the highest category (endangered) than animals: 766 plants and 486 animals.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency maintains a webpage that lists all the endangered and threatened plant species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Almost all listings are at the species level, but a few are subspecies or varieties.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Historians attribute this new-found concern for imperiled plants to ongoing global treaty negotiations (especially in 1972 and 1973) toward what would eventually be adopted in 1975 under the title, Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Prior to this time, attention to the conservation needs of native plants had been stalled by complications that do not pertain to animals.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] How to adequately distinguish plants illegally collected in the wild from plants propagated from seeds or cuttings taken from horticultural specimens was among the points of contention.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Ultimately, federal authority over enforcement of endangered plant protections has centered on regulation of interstate commerce of such plants.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Because movement of seeds and seedlings by this group was noncommercial and based on horticulturally produced specimens, there was no legal apparatus to halt their actions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Another distinction is that, when an animal is listed as endangered, "taking" of that animal (by capture or killing) becomes a violation of the Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For plants, "taking" occurs only within the boundaries of federal properties.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Even so, states may choose to legislate and enforce prohibitions even on private lands, as occurred in 2023 when the State of California passed a law that prevented killing or removal of the western variety of Joshua tree wherever it was found.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Climate change risk was a key factor in the determination.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act distinguished two grades of species for listing: "**endangered**" and a lesser category called "**threatened**".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency maintains a webpage that lists all the endangered and threatened animal species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The set is organized into ten groups and appears on the webpage in this order: amphibians, arachnids, birds, clams, crustaceans, fishes, insects, mammals, reptiles, and snails.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency maintains a webpage for the public to access the complete **list of endangered animals** and a separate webpage for **endangered plants**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The agency also maintains a webpage that lists in tabular format all the species of plants and animals that have been "**reclassified**" and when that occurred.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Total entries on that list were 65 as of February 2025.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Some entries are just populations rather than full species or subspecies.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] For example, at the beginning of the list are two populations of California tiger salamander; one is in Sonoma County and the other in Santa Barbara County.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Both were reclassified from endangered to threatened in August 2004.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] There is also an online webpage that documents in tabular format all species that have been "**delisted**." One of the columns is used to distinguish whether the species is foreign or domestic.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] A key provision of the 1973 Act was that "preventing extinction" would no longer be sufficient.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Rather, "recovery" of listed species, such that "delisting" could ensue, became a stated goal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The complications and controversies arising during recovery plan development and approval have meant that the two-year deadline for producing a plan after a new species is listed have sometimes met with long delays.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The 1973 Act introduced the concept of what is now called "critical habitat" in only one brief passage.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The 1978 amendments also provided for the consideration of economic impacts when designating critical habitat, and provided a mechanism for excluding critical habitat where the benefits of exclusion would outweigh the benefits of designating the area as critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As will be seen in the "Controversies" section, this provision is sometimes challenging to implement for both scientific and political reasons, as when more than a million acres of critical habitat was proposed in 2024 for the rusty patched bumblebee and officially adopted in 2026.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of June 2026, 995 critical habitat documents pertaining to all species are listed and linked online by the agency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The Act, as amended, directs all federal agencies to use their authorities to help conserve listed species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Documents that are published in advance of action decisions include environmental impact statements and formal biological opinions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Those that pertain to lands that include critical habitat designations provide the grounds for developing site-specific restrictions or requirements for mitigating impacts on listed species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of April 2026, the **Biological Opinions** webpage lists 4,736 entries.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Some of those biological opinions and reports aggregate a number of species into a single document to support interagency cooperation and the development or updating of official recovery plans.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The central feature of the Act is listing, protecting, and recovering domestic species of animals and plants that are threatened or endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] Additionally, Section 8 of the Act directs that international treaties and conventions pertaining to imperiled species are also to be implemented.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The same year that the U.S. endangered species legislation was being shaped, an international effort to enact something similar was underway.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The **Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora**, abbreviated as CITES, is a multilateral treaty to protect the plants and animals that are largely imperiled by international trade.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] It was drafted as a result of a resolution adopted in 1963 at a meeting of members of the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] The convention was opened for signature in 1973 and CITES entered into force in July 1975.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of 2025, roughly 6,610 species of animals and 34,310 species of plants are protected internationally against over-exploitation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] In 1992, the Supreme Court ruled that citizens do not have standing to sue the federal government for providing funds to other countries for uses that may harm foreign species that are listed as endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p01] As of 2023, those deadlines still nominally apply, but in practice it is rare for a petitioner to approach the judicial system to force a decision before the agency is able to finish the job on its own timetable.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Endangered Species Act of 1973 (ESA) is regarded as "one of the most powerful and controversial environmental laws in the United States." In 2023, with the Act achieving its 50th anniversary, journalists were prompted to report on the Act's outcomes and controversies.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Congressional overturning of several recent listings and ability to hamper implementation by restricting agency funding were among the points mentioned by some media.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An academic review paper in 2008 reported that the Act had become "a social, legal, and political battleground" and that "the scientific question of whether the ESA works effectively to protect species remains open." Indeed, endless litigation has become a defining feature of ESA implementation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Specific challenges and long-term controversies are summarized in this multi-part section.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Support for learning and evaluating the history of ESA implementation is an online system maintained by the federal government whereby a great variety of reports published during the five decades of endangered species implementation can be accessed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The numbers and complexity of those documents are the focus of the fourth topical section included below.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For now, the list shown here is just one section of the gateway webpage for accessing reports by species, by region, and by other factors.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] "**ECOS: Environmental Conservation Online System**" is the name of the governmental website, and the gateway page is **ECOS Species Reports**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] All the decisions and reports and supplementary materials pertaining to implementation of the Act are posted by the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service through that system.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because some of the challenges and controversies arising from implementation of the federal Act entail interactions with various state governmental priorities and programs, it is important to establish the background of state jurisdiction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, downlisting of the Chiricahua leopard frog from endangered to threatened is attributed to state-level efforts by Arizona and New Mexico.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The need for a federal listing of the Mardon skipper butterfly was avoided, owing to cooperative early efforts by the states of Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In practice through the decades, the federal-state relationship has not always been congenial.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Elected officials at both federal and state levels sometimes escalate calls for outright devolving endangered species management to the states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An overall federal policy for collaboration, however, is not achievable because the kinds and scale of species-protective laws, regulations, and implementation priorities vary enormously among the states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As well, only California and Oregon authorize citizens to petition for state-level listings, and distinctions prevail in matters concerning critical habitat designations and the degree to which species protections can impinge on land use choices by private owners.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Nothing prevents a state from issuing stricter regulations for a federal listed species within its boundaries.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 2018 survey of state laws found that Illinois, Massachusetts, and Wisconsin "even go beyond the ESA in their protective measures." As well, nothing prevents a state from listing a species that the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service formally decides against.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An example of federal-state tensions occurred in California in July 2023.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It was then that California enacted its own "Western Joshua Tree Conservation Act." This halted all sales of the western species of *Yucca brevifolia*, while instituting a permit process for any proposed removal, harm, or trimming of the species on private lands.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The legislature itself chose to pass this law after the federal agency had formally decided against listing on two occasions: August 2019 and March 2023.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The second decision had been forced by a 2021 court remand of the 2019 decision, and was based on a "Species Status Assessment Report" (173 pages) that had been published by the agency the prior month.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An important distinction of California's 2023 Joshua Tree statute is that it did not confer even state-level listing of this plant as threatened or endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Instead, a highly collaborative "**Western Joshua Tree Conservation Plan**" would be established and implemented (the draft was published December 2024).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This would pre-empt the need for California's state-level Fish and Game Commission to decide upon an already pending listing petition in accordance with the California Endangered Species Act (CESA).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Despite the State of California's initiative, a national environmental organization (WildEarth Guardians), went to the federal court system again.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In May 2025, the court ruled in their behalf.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In October 2025, the State of California once again took actions to supersede federal ESA implementation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] That same month, the California Department of Fish and Wildlife euthanized four federally endangered wolves that had recently established in a cattle ranching part of the state.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The petitioning, listing, and recovery planning stages prescribed in the Act have a history not only of contentiousness but of delays and setbacks owing to all three branches of the federal government sometimes becoming involved.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This is especially the case when a federal listing would apply to an animal whose widely dispersed populations are declining over a vast landscape.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Potential listing of the Lesser prairie-chicken is one such example.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 1995 the Center for Biological Diversity, along with other conservation groups, petitioned for listing the lesser prairie-chicken.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Agency recognition of the bird as a "candidate species" in 1998 deferred formal review while the agency worked its way through a backlog of previous petitions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In an effort to achieve habitat improvement agreements with state and private landowners prior to (and possibly thereby precluding) a listing decision, a "voluntary prelisting conservation program" was launched in 2010 — not by the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Department of Interior (which includes the Fish and Wildlife Service), but by the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This government-led project was unusual for an at-risk species in that it was launched with the expressed intent to promote the long-term sustainability of ranching operations while improving the population and occupied territory of the lesser prairie-chicken.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Conservation groups were keen on collaborative agreements not only for the wellbeing of this grassland bird but because of its ecological role as an umbrella species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Protecting the habitat needs of an umbrella species thereby also protects the habitat of dozens of other at-risk species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] That project did not advance well enough to preclude a listing petition in 2012, which resulted in a formal listing as "threatened" in 2014.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This action was overturned by the courts in 2015, when it was challenged by business interests associated with oil and gas extraction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Conservation groups resumed petitioning for listing of the species, with the executive branch repeatedly deferring a decision until 2022.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It was then that a listing was finalized that classified the southern population as endangered and the northern population as threatened.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, in 2023 Congress passed a bill that negated the listing, which was promptly vetoed by President Biden.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2025, a federal court in Texas ruled in favor of a case filed by the State of Texas and several petroleum companies that pointed to problems in the 2022 listing decision.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Trump Administration did not defend against the lawsuit and even requested the court to overturn the listing rule.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In sum, from 1998 to early 2026, two executive agencies of the federal government, two judicial actions, and one attempt by Congress to overturn a listing decision all played roles in how the Endangered Species Act would be applied to the conservation of the Lesser prairie-chicken.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An even more complicated example is the gray wolf, as presented in a 2020 report by the Congressional Research Service subtitled, "A Case Study in Listing and Delisting Challenges." Details of this report appear in a delisting section later on this page.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The ESA, as amended, specifies the use of science in two distinct areas of decision-making.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] First, determinations whether to list (and downlist or delist) species must be made "solely" on the basis of science, without consideration of how a listing decision might adversely affect other national or regional priorities.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Second, all agency decisions on managing species that are already listed must be made using "the best available science." Together, these two mandates have generated considerable discord and lawsuits on a variety of agency decisions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] To begin, the statute requires that agency decisions on listings must not be influenced by political, corporate, or citizen concerns that such listings could impinge on access to natural resources on public lands or how private landowners choose to manage their own properties.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Rather, listings are to be based "solely" on the science.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] But even peer-reviewed science publications can be at odds, thus offering grounds for opposing parties to each present rational arguments that their position is more in line with the science than that of their opponents.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Additional points of contention arise when "the best available science" is clearly deficient.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In these circumstances even the Information Quality Act guidelines issued by the federal Office of Management and Budget, along with the scientific integrity policies of the implementing agencies, may offer little support for resolving debates and thus preventing lawsuits.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] If staff time is already overwhelmed by existing legal requirements for decision-making and if the budget lacks capacity for hiring research by contractors, decisions will have to be made despite even large unknowns in the data and conclusions of science.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Parties who strongly disagree with the agency decision may then utilize the Administrative Procedure Act to contest the outcome in court, if they can construct a good case that established agency norms for decision-making were violated.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Overturn of the Chevron deference by the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supreme Court in 2024 may have amplified opportunities for judicial scrutiny of agency decisions to the point that even "the best available science" aspects can be argued in court.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Among the most polarizing provisions in the Act are the rights awarded to citizens (and their interest groups) to compel the agency to make listing decisions, to specify "critical habitat", and then to challenge in court such decisions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] To begin, citizens are authorized to submit petitions proposing the listing of new species and to have those petitions officially responded to in accordance with deadlines set forth in the Act, as amended.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decisions to list (or not to list), along with the degree of protection granted (endangered or threatened), are then vulnerable to citizen litigation in federal courts.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In practice, agency decisions are sometimes challenged by biodiversity proponents who assert that "the best available science" would compel stronger listing protections.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decisions are also sometimes challenged by oppositional interest groups, notably by those grounded in business, extractive industry, or landowner rights perspectives.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A review article published in 2025 on lessons learned from implementation of the ESA reports on how the "best available science" understandings have evolved through time, including examples (notably, population viability analysis) where experts continue to disagree.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supreme Court in 2024 may have amplified opportunities for citizens pro and con to obtain judicial scrutiny of agency decisions grounded in arguable "best available science" and the unavoidably ambiguous standards written into the statute.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Citizen suits are not unique to the Endangered Species Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 2004 paper reported that "sixteen of the nation's principal federal environmental laws invite citizens to sue" to force agencies to perform mandatory duties.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Disagreement amplified when some environmental interest groups began submitting mega-petitions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2011 a "mega-settlement" was achieved by the agency, WildEarth Guardians, and another biodiversity advocate group, Center for Biological Diversity.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The settlement required FWS to take action on pending petitions for 757 species over the next seven years.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In exchange, the two environmental groups agreed to limit lawsuits filed against the agency so that efforts could be focused on trying to accomplish the terms of the agreement.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The following year, however, the Center for Biological Diversity submitted a single petition for listing a total of 53 amphibians and reptiles spanning a range of 45 states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The list of citizen petitioners included two well-known ecological scientists: Edward O.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] From a practical standpoint, citizen suits are unlikely to be launched frivolously because of the costs of attorney time, coupled with the need to obtain a win in order to benefit from court-ordered reimbursement of legal expenses.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] United States Fish and Wildlife Service*, Edward Poitevent and his family have owned land in St.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Tammany Parish, Louisiana, since the end of the Civil War.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The family relies on this land for their livelihood, having signed a 90-year lease in the 1950s to preserve their property.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In the 1990s, the Weyerhaeuser Company acquired this lease for timber operations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2012, the USFWS designated over 1,500 acres of Poitevent's property as critical habitat for the dusky gopher frog, a species that had not been sighted in Louisiana for 50 years.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The nearest population of this frog was located nearly 70 miles away in Mississippi, leading many to argue that the designation was an arbitrary bureaucratic decision that restricted Poitevent's property rights and froze an estimated $34 million in economic activity.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supreme court affirming that the Fish and Wildlife Service exceeded its statutory authority in making the critical habitat designation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Marina Point Development Corp.*, the plaintiffs filed citizen suit actions under the Clean Water Act (CWA) and the Endangered Species Act (ESA) against a developer, claiming violations by the construction project.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] After the district court ruled in favor of the plaintiffs, the developer appealed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] On appeal, the court found that the plaintiffs had not met the 60-day notice requirement for their CWA claims and that the ESA claims were moot due to the delisting of the bald eagle in 2007.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As a result, the appellate court ordered the vacatur of both the district court's judgment and its opinion.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Bernhardt*, Ken Klemm managed a 4,000-acre bison ranch for over two decades, focusing on bison grazing.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service regulations that treated species at minimal extinction risk similarly to those facing imminent danger.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2019, the Department of Interior reformed the Endangered Species Act (ESA), reinstating a two-step protection system to alleviate burdens on landowners like Klemm.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A lawsuit from 17 states and environmental groups challenged these reforms, leading Klemm to intervene.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] On July 5, 2022, a district court vacated the 2019 reforms without evaluating their legality.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Ninth Circuit subsequently ruled that federal regulations cannot be rescinded without judicial review, allowing the 2019 rules to remain while the agency undergoes a formal amendment process.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Citizens (including non-governmental organizations) are empowered to petition a species (or distinct population of a vertebrate species) to be designated as threatened or endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decision documents (first in draft, then in final) are posted in the Federal Register.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Draft decisions are to be posted for comment within two years, but in practice it often takes the agency much longer.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the statute directs the agency to use "the best available science" when evaluating a petition, no new scientific research needs to be conducted before issuing a response.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Even so, staff time and resources may be substantial, partly to ensure that the resulting decision derives from a document that can allay disappointed stakeholders from going to court.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Decisions on petitions have been most challenged when the Center for Biological Diversity or WildEarth Guardians submit "mega-petitions" that request decisions on scores of species at the same time.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Failure to meet the regulatory deadlines could subject the agency to judicial review.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Only Congress can forestall those kinds of lawsuits.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Thus, in 2011 the Fish and Wildlife Service itself requested Congress to impose a cap on the portion of the agency's budget that could be spent responding to petitions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A **recovery plan** (with or without critical habitat designations) is the major document prepared by the agency following a listing decision of threatened or endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Reviews of the plan, with updates if merited, are to be performed every five years.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The statutory requirement for other federal agencies to act in ways supportive of listed species is generally referred to as "**agency consultation**." This is where the decision-making, documentation, and public participation becomes more complex.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Congressional Research Service (CRS) produced (and periodically updates) a detailed online document whose purpose is to make the Act and its implementation outcomes understandable to members and staff of the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Titled, "The Endangered Species Act: Overview and Implementation," the document has lengthy sections pertaining to the complexities of and distinctions between **Section 7 "Interagency Consultation"** and **Section 10 "Exceptions"**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Legally required written documents that result are known as "**Incidental Take Statements**" (ITS), which is an outcome of Section 7 of the Act, and two documents arising from Section 10: **Incidental Take Permits** (ITP) and **Habitat Conservation Plans** (HCP).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A two-page version of just the "Section 7 Consultation" process, requirements, and document outcomes was published by the CRS in 2023.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In it, one learns distinctions between a "**biological assessment**" and a "**biological opinion**" (BiOp).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The latter may contain an "incidental take statement" (ITS) if an endangered species could experience "jeopardy" if the action moves forward.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Environmental Impact Statements (EIS) and subsequent permitting actions are administered by the Environmental Protection Agency, with requirements for consulting with the Fish and Wildlife Service within specified time parameters.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The same holds for actions and permitting authorities of the Bureau of Land Management, Forest Service, and Army Corps of Engineers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Entities seeking development permits on federal lands may be required to develop "**Habitat Conservation Plans**" (HCP) that may include mitigation efforts, monitoring, and even supporting additional field science.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] HCP documents can be accessed individually by the development project title through the ECOS portal.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, the "Criterion Wind Power" project has an individual page.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Its permit to proceed was issued in 2014 for a duration of 21 years.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Subsidiary links include two versions of the HCP, two Biological Opinions, a NEPA-EA, a NEPA-FONSI, and a "Set of Findings".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Finally, although not subject to public comment requirements via draft publication in the *Federal Register*, the Fish and Wildlife Service has been making the recovery plan stage less complex by creating policy-free and science-rich "**Species Status Assessments**" (SSA).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These are posted on a dedicated ECOS portal, with summary statements later embedded into the formal, and policy-rich recovery plan documents.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Controversy sometimes roils when the timing of a petition to list a new species overlaps with plans for or initiation of a development project that could be impeded by such a listing.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A news editorial marking the 50th anniversary of the Act suggested that "the ESA became the weapon of choice for environmental groups seeking to stop projects or tear down others.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Lawsuits by the score have been filed over projects large and small, setting off ill feelings toward environmental groups." A prominent example of this dynamic was the listing of the coastal California gnatcatcher.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Some observers opined that the impetus for listing was in part borne out of the species being considered a "flagship" for the coastal sage scrub ecosystem of southern California—an area subject to significant pressure for housing development.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the Act allowed species to be listed as endangered without consideration of the economic consequences, it soon became and continues to be controversial.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Costs conferred on private landowners and various industries may come in the form of lost opportunity or slowing down operations to comply with the regulations put forth in the Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Notably, in 1978 the listing of a tiny fish (snail darter) shut down for several years construction of a dam that was already underway on the Little Tennessee River.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] More broadly, the requirement to consult with the relevant agencies on federal projects has at times slowed operations by the oil and gas industry, including exploration or development on federal lands rich in fossil fuels.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Due to political backlash stemming from the snail darter decision, in 1978 Congress amended the ESA to be more sensitive to costs.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The 1978 amendments also amended the **Section 7 consultation process** to authorize FWS and NMFS to allow projects that may affect listed species or habitat to continue if there are "reasonable and prudent alternatives" that minimize adverse impacts.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These amendments to the critical habitat and Section 7 consultation processes (along with additional amendments made in 1982) were designed to offset the consequences of the cost-neutral process for the initial listing of species, and to improve flexibility in the ESA's application.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Notwithstanding the 1978 and 1982 amendments, one widely held opinion remains that the protections afforded to listed species curtail economic activity.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In the extreme, economic consequences can induce perverse incentives by which landowners actively curtail their lands from attracting endangered species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] An example in the eastern USA pertains to the endangered red-cockaded woodpecker.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 1995 study of some 1,000 privately owned forest plots within the range of the woodpecker found that when landowners observed pine growth maturing to a stage in which it might attract nesting woodpeckers, they were more likely to harvest – regardless of timber prices at the time.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This is a form of intentional habitat destruction for avoiding economic consequences.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] By 2024, however, recovery actions had gone well enough for the federal agency to downlist the species from endangered to threatened.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Downlisting was achieved in large part because of a linked pair of innovative conservation documents negotiated between landowners and the federal agency: **Conservation Benefit Agreement (CBA)** and **Enhancement of Survival (EOS)** permit.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Legislators have expressed that the ESA has been "weaponized," particularly against western states, constraining state government choices about the use of public lands.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The case of the protracted dispute over the greater sage-grouse is one such example, and the spotted owl is another.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In the extreme is the largely western saying pertaining to endangered animals, such as wolves: "shoot, shovel, and shut up." Rep.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Some economists have stated that finding a way to reduce such perverse incentives would lead to more effective protection of endangered species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One suggestion for ending perverse incentives would be to compensate property owners for protecting endangered species, rather than having an endangered species regarded as a potential financial loss.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] 4. would give landowners a reason to maintain their property in species-friendly condition.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As well, while the standard to prevent jeopardy or adverse modification, under Section 7 of the ESA, applies only to federal activities (which can, however, include private activities that require a federal permit), entirely non-federal activities are subject to Section 10 of the Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] To work toward conservation solutions before perverse incentives develop, the "Conservation Without Conflict" initiative and coalition was formed in 2017, with guidance presented in a series of eight steps.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Other collaborations supported by nongovernmental organizations focus on ranching and forestry stewardship initiatives.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Supreme Court ruling in *Tennessee Valley Authority v.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Ever since the Supreme Court ruling in the snail darter case, interest groups with a biocentric focus have had strong grounding for challenging agency listing decisions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Another consequence of the snail darter ruling is that formal listing decisions sometimes include lengthy expositions of scientific details.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This way, it is clear that the "best available science" has indeed been consulted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A highly controversial, and thus lengthy, listing decision was issued in 2022.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It pertains to a small flowering plant in the desert of southwest Nevada.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The published document in the *Federal Register* that establishes Tiehm's buckwheat as an endangered species is 33 pages long, inclusive of a "critical habitat" designation for 910 acres that was simultaneously issued.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Six of the total pages are responses to each of 29 comments elicited when the required draft of the listing was published.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The foundational document that established the "best available science" for making the listing decision was previously published as a "**Species Status Assessment**", which in itself was 80 pages long in PDF format.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A recent example of competing priorities happened when the federal government was compelled to make a listing decision on a petition.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2019 the Center for Biological Diversity petitioned to have a small flowering plant in Nevada listed as endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A mining project by Ioneer, an Australian company, was already preparing the site for extracting lithium and boron.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Environmental interests were thus divided between those focused on species protection and those advocating for electric vehicles, which require lithium as the key component of the lightest-weight batteries.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] While economic concerns and priorities are restricted from playing a role in governmental listing decisions, the 1978 amendments to the Act did make it possible for these matters to impinge on the designation of critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the endangered listing decision and critical habitat specification occurred in the same document in 2022, this resulted in something unusual: Both the Center for Biological Diversity (CBD) and the mining company posted support for the decision.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] CBD was enthusiastic about the endangered listing.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Ioneer already had developed a plan to begin mining that would not interfere with the 910 acres of critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In this case, the critical habitat and its surrounds were entirely on public lands managed by the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It thus fell to that agency, in consultation with the Fish and Wildlife Service, to make the final decisions about whether, where, and how the mine could proceed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The Bureau granted approval October 2024.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Numerous associated documents can be found on the agency's webpage for the Rhyolite Ridge Project, with all the underlying reports and documents fulfilling the requirements of the National Environmental Policy Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The approval was preceded by a 2023 "Public Scoping Report" that was 15 pages, plus more than 100 pages of appendices.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Ioneer also has a publicly accessible website, where it publishes all the documents preceding and related to the permit decision.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One of the links goes to "Ioneer's Buckwheat Protection Plan Summary: Proposed Conservation Measures for Tiehm's Buckwheat and Critical Habitat." Another page on the website describes the company's past and future conservation efforts.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The 50th anniversary of the ESA was in December 2023.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As the time approached, interest groups and journalists began writing about the results of its implementation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As of August that year, an aggregate of 1,780 species had been cumulatively listed as "**endangered**" or a lesser category of "**threatened**".
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] While 99% of the total species were still alive, critics pointed out that only 64 species had improved enough to be declared as **recovered** and thus removed from the list (**delisted**).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A data point on the positive side was that a different set of 64 species had improved enough to be **downlisted** from endangered to threatened.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Among the most celebrated successes is that of the American alligator.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] This reptile was listed as endangered in 1967.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Twenty years later it was delisted as fully recovered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, because of its resemblance to its endangered saltwater relative in Florida, the American crocodile, hunting and commercial trade regulations have been maintained for this species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The most controversial measure of effectiveness, however, pertained to the published number of cumulatively listed species that had gone **extinct**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As the autumn of 2023 began, the official number was 11.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] But another 23 species had gone missing for so long that in September 2021 the agency had published a 41-page draft ruling in the *Federal Register* to officially declare those 23 species extinct.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It took two years for the agency to finalize its proposed ruling, but in October 2023 the controversy was settled.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The agency ruled as extinct 21 of the 23 species it had proposed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Declared extinct were Bachman's warbler, which had been native to Florida and South Carolina, along with nine tropical birds (8 in Hawaii and 1 in Guam).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Hope still remained for one bird, the Ivory-billed woodpecker.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The only other species that remained listed as endangered was a Hawaiian plant in the mint family.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Another controversy has been ongoing for more than three decades.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Some have argued that the recovery of imperiled flesh-eating birds (notably, the bald eagle, brown pelican, and peregrine falcon) should be attributed to the 1972 ban of the pesticide DDT by the EPA, rather than the Endangered Species Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Supporters of the Act argue that listing these species as endangered led to additional actions that were also crucial for species recovery (i.e., captive breeding, habitat protection, and protection from disturbance).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Among the most difficult species to protect are mussels because they depend on adequate amounts of clean and flowing freshwater.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Home to approximately 300 mussel species, the eastern region of the USA is the center of global diversity for these freshwater molluscs.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, 65 percent of them are threatened or endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The 1988 Congressional amendments to the Act included a new section, Section 18, to aid effectiveness evaluations by having each of the two implementing agencies periodically report cumulative federal funding (and, to some degree, state funding) on a species-by-species basis.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As of 2026, the agency webpage titled "Endangered and Threatened Species Expenditures Reports" lists and links annual reports from fiscal year 1989 through 2020, but for no later years.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The above section on "effectiveness" of the Act is examined here as to why it is that recovery, and thus delistings, are rare.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A widely used statistic supporting effectiveness of the Act is that 99 percent of listed species have not gone extinct.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Full recovery may thus be slow, but substantial progress is evidenced when a species is **downlisted** from endangered to threatened.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, National Marine Fisheries Service lists eight species (or populations of a species) as among the most at risk of extinction in the near future.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These animals are the Atlantic salmon; the Central California Coast coho salmon; the Cook Inlet beluga whale; the Hawaiian monk seal; the Pacific leatherback sea turtle; the Sacramento River winter-run chinook salmon; the southern resident population of killer whale; and the white abalone.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Human activities are presented as the primary cause of extinction threats for all these species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] While the two implementing agencies have a combined record of changing species status from threatened to endangered on nine occasions, the number of status improvements from endangered to threatened is greater.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] On the opposing side of the spectrum, a foundation associated with the Western Caucus of U.S. senators and representatives issued a 116-page report in 2023 that points to data and statements made by the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service during the past half-century that can be interpreted as disputing proclamations of success.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Specifically, statements of numbers of species "recovered" do not distinguish between those delisted owing to actual improvement in populations versus those for which the original population numbers were later found to have been greatly underestimated.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Had the science been more in line with reality at the start, this report claims 36 of the 62 species reported by the agency as officially recovered would not have achieved listing at the outset.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Controversy also develops when the science used to support a delisting decision differs from the numerical population thresholds included in the **species recovery plan**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] For example, the listing of the California sea otter has been controversial with fishermen who contend that the sea otter's expansion from Monterey into Southern California waters has resulted in a dramatic reduction in sea urchin, abalone, and other commercially valuable species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These impacts led certain fishermen groups to petition the government to delist the sea otter.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The petition argued that delisting is appropriate because, among other reasons, the sea otter's population goals, as contained in the most recent recovery plan, have been met.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The government, however, denied the petition.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A 2012 court case upheld the agency decision, ruling that published recovery criteria are not legally binding for later delisting decisions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Accordingly, during the early 2020s an even more controversial agency response against a delisting petition was supported by that court decision.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It pertained to the grizzly bear in six distinct populations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] In 2024 a "new metric to evaluate recovery progress" was published by 13 coauthors.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Listing of a species "triggers two overlapping types of conservation measures: extinction prevention and recovery actions." An official document required by the Act has come to be known as a recovery plan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Besides alleged funding inadequacies, several inherent problems have been pointed to for delays in agency translation of scientific findings into actions beyond extinction prevention and thus actively toward species recovery.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One such problem is the "knowledge—action boundary" that distinguishes conservation scientists from conservation managers.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] That is, how can scientific scholarship be made actionable, and thereby contribute directly to forward-moving policies and practices?
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] "Fear of failure in conservation" is another factor that contributes to agency and manager hesitancy to undertake recovery actions for which there is no certainty of success.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] There are two reasons why scientists themselves may abstain from recommending actions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] One is fear that making such recommendations may compromise their status as objective researchers whose conclusions can be trusted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] A second is fear that a recommended action that is undertaken but then fails may injure their reputation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] These fears may be heightened when recommendations pertain to a species for which controversy has developed or one whose population has declined so drastically that any manipulation of the species or its habitat may later be denounced as contributing to its further decline or extinction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Species recovery is slowed by inherent complexities.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish & Wildlife Service maintains a webpage that sets forth the **stages of the recovery process**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Fish and Wildlife Service itself has recognized that specifying in a written plan the actions to achieve recovery goals falls short of ensuring that such actions will take place.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Statutory and regulatory requirements for producing an initial **recovery plan** are still fulfilled, including opportunities for public comments.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The plan is to be written and published in the customary way, and it continues to be subject to the "five year review" process.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] However, two new kinds of working documents can be developed, posted, and updated as needed for each listed species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] The first updatable document is a **Species Status Assessment (SSA)**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] It is "a biological risk assessment to aid decision makers who must use the best available scientific information to make policy decisions under the ESA." As new papers are published and rigorous data collected, the SSA can be updated and reposted as warranted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] As of April 2026, 455 listed or petitioned species have had an SSA completed and posted on the FWS aggregate list.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] SSA updates may, in turn, stimulate changes in the third part of the new framework: the **Recovery Implementation Strategy (RIS)**.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Because the agency had been criticized for lacking "clear distinctions between science input and policy application," four FWS agency scientists along with two colleagues in the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Geological Survey published a paper in 2018 in the *Journal of Fish and Wildlife Management*.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p02] Titled, "Development of a Species Status Assessment Process for Decisions under the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] With or without listing, there are opportunities for stakeholders themselves to begin actions on their own.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This especially applies to habitat improvements.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] If suitable habitat for a species can be found on private, state, municipal, or tribal lands, there is no need to wait for the federal agency to offer or specify in-place actions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The parties can expand and improve such habitats on their own.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] While there are legal limitations on what citizens and other stakeholders can do directly for listed animal species, the field is wide open for obtaining horticulturally produced seeds and specimens of listed plants and then conducting plantings on their own.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A well-known example is a network of citizens who call themselves Torreya Guardians.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Florida Torreya is a glacial relict species of subcanopy tree that was listed as endangered in 1984.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Since 2004, the citizen group has been using seeds from mature plantings on private lands in North Carolina (and since 2018 also from their own plantings in Ohio) to engage in a form of assisted migration poleward of this climate-endangered plant.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Prior to listing of a species, stakeholders who wish to act in its behalf have freedom to engage with not only habitat but with the species itself.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A well-known example entails actions taken in behalf of the subalpine Whitebark Pine of the northern Rocky Mountains soon after vast stands suddenly began to die in Yellowstone National Park and elsewhere.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A petition for listing was submitted in 2008, but status as "threatened" was not conferred until 2022.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] By then, collaboration among concerned parties was well underway without agency direction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supportive research and actions were undertaken by the conservation organization American Forests as well as a new organization specific to the tree: the Whitebark Pine Ecosystem Foundation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Other collaborators include research scientists within the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Forest Service, geneticists at the University of California, Davis, and the Confederated Salish and Kootenai Tribes.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Bureau of Land Management and the National Park Service were also involved in consultation prior to listing by the agency in charge of endangered species: the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 188-page **Species Status Assessment** published in 2021 aggregates the scientific information on which the policy decision to list the species as threatened was based.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Controversy is also apparent, though rare, when stakeholders entail activists who regard the "political-economic regime" not as the source of solutions but as "the root cause of biodiversity loss." In such instances guerrilla rewilding of rare species has been known to occur.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The 1982 amendments to Section 10 of the Act authorized collaborative engagement of the implementing agencies with landowners in producing Habitat Conservation Plans.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Such a plan is a required part of an application for an Incidental Take Permit, issued under the Act to private and other nonfederal entities undertaking projects that might result in harm to a listed species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The intent is to deter controversy by building into the plan practices for minimizing harm to listed species and their core habitat needs (including seasonal peaks in use).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A validated plan then absolves the landowner (or developer) from harms that may incidentally occur to the species, when following the plan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Securing landowner pledges of habitat enhancement measures during the planning process can serve to defuse opposition from the public and other stakeholders.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Plan preparation is generally initiated and produced by a nonfederal entity: private landowner, state government, local government.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of 2021, more than 700 habitat conservation plans were in force for listed species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A leading example is the plan produced by the state of Massachusetts in 2016 to reduce conflicts between a type of beach-nesting shorebird, piping plover, and recreational beach users along the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Such plans also apply to the red-cockaded woodpecker of forests in the southeastern states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 2024 a new program went into effect: **Conservation Benefits Agreement** (CBA).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] It combined and streamlined two previous opportunities for landowners to initiate their own conservation projects and thereby obtain assurances that stabilize how federal policies apply to their actions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An example of a CBA that was approved in 2025 was initiated by a minerals corporation with lands in southeastern Arizona.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The voluntary agreement benefits three endangered fish species (spikedace, loach minnow, and Gila chub) and one threatened snake (narrow-headed garter snake).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The agreement will remain in effect for 50 years.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2019 report found that the Fish and Wildlife Service faced a backlog of more than 500 species that have been determined to potentially warrant protection.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2022 report pointed to severe population declines while species await listing decisions as a major problem impeding eventual recovery success.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The decision to list or defer listing of a petitioned species is supposed to take no more than 2 years after a petition is filed.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] However, on average it takes the agency 12 years to finalize a decision.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An analysis published in 2016 by the Ecological Society of America found that approximately 50 species may have gone extinct while awaiting a listing decision.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Additional funding might enable the agency to direct more resources toward biological assessments of petitioned species and determine if they merit a listing decision.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An additional issue is that species still listed under the Act may already be extinct.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] For example, the IUCN Red List declared the Scioto madtom extinct in 2013.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This freshwater species had last been seen alive in its small native range in Ohio in 1957.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] However, it was not until 2023 that the FWS officially declared this catfish as extinct.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of February 2025, the Fish and Wildlife Service online system that catalogs all current listing proposals that have not yet been processed shows there are 65 outstanding domestic and foreign species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The list aggregates the proposed species into broad taxonomic types.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Counting only the domestic (not the foreign) species on the list, there are: 5 amphibians, 3 birds, 13 freshwater clams, 3 crustaceans (crayfish), 8 fishes, 3 flowering plants, 7 insects, 2 mammals (1 rat and 1 bat), 12 reptiles, and 2 snails.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Bipartisan support for the Endangered Species Act of 1973 began to unravel almost immediately when a tiny fish native to Tennessee, the snail darter, tested the strong biocentric focus of the Act.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Elsewhere on this page, and also on a distinct wikipedia page, the snail darter controversy is dealt with at length.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Here it is important to mention that in 2025, tools for making taxonomic determinations had advanced to the point that the snail darter is no longer regarded as a species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] From the beginning, implementation of the ESA of 1973 is based on "the best available science," beginning with taxonomic classification.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The petitioned group of organisms must first qualify as a bona fide species or subspecies.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Isolated populations or varieties of otherwise common species may be considered for listing only if they are vertebrates.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Given the evolutionary processes by which species arise and continue to change, there is no consensus that could provide a singular definition or standard for the agency to use.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Classification is therefore determined on a case-by-case basis and generally secured by publication in an academic journal — which itself is vulnerable to publish-or-perish motivations that can lead to what is called taxonomic inflation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This in itself can make the posting of a listing decision vulnerable to public attack.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supreme Court in 2024 may have amplified classification as grounds for litigation by opponents of endangered species listings.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] To begin, improvements in conservation genomics established that the already-listed red wolf evolved as a hybrid of native gray wolves and coyotes who interbred in the eastern states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The problem compounded when the red wolf population managed on a coastal island became populous enough for geographic range experimentation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Individuals released onto the mainland routinely interbred with the far more populous coyotes, and genetic swamping ensued.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Other listed animals embroiled in hybridization controversies include the golden-winged warbler, westslope cutthroat trout, the wood bison, and the eastern massasauga rattlesnake.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An example for plants in which a taxonomic decision required listing as a distinct species a globe mallow in Arizona concerns the genus *Sphaeralcea*.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Only once has hybridization been an intentional recovery action, known as genetic rescue.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This was applied to the Florida panther when cougars from Texas were intentionally released into its habitat to counter ongoing decline owing to inbreeding depression.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This openness to using hybridization to outright save a species contrasted with the agency's decision to deny cross-breeding of the dusky seaside sparrow with its sister species: Scott's seaside sparrow.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2025 review paper reports that naturally occurring hybridization that is already happening "threatens to swamp" these listed taxa: northern spotted owl, bull trout, California tiger salamander, and red wolf.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Because habitat loss is regarded as the primary threat to most imperiled species, Section 4 of the Endangered Species Act of 1973 allowed the Fish and Wildlife Service (FWS) and National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) to designate specific areas as protected "Critical Habitat" zones.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The designation of critical habitat does not affect land ownership.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] It does not allow the government to take or manage private property, nor to establish a refuge, reserve, preserve, or other conservation area.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Critical habitat designation does not allow unauthorized government access to private land.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Such designation can, however, severely restrict activities allowable on private lands.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 1978, Congress amended the law to make critical habitat designation a mandatory requirement for all threatened and endangered species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] To offset some of the consequences of this amendment, and to improve flexibility in the ESA's application, the 1978 amendments also added economics into the process of determining such designation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The controversy did arise and thus the 1982 amendment to the Act explicitly prohibited similar economic considerations when determining the status of a species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In designating critical habitat, the needs of open space for individual and population growth, food, water, light or other nutritional requirements, breeding sites, seed germination and dispersal needs, and lack of disturbances are considered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As itemized within a 2008 review paper on the Endangered Species Act, designation of critical habitat is the first priority for agency action following listing of a species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Not all recovery plans, however, specify critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Most provisions of the ESA revolve around preventing extinction.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Critical habitat is one of the few that focus on recovery.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2005 paper published in the journal *BioScience* concluded that species afforded critical habitat are twice as likely to be recovering than are species without critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2016 report published by the Ecological Society of America stated that data were inconclusive on this matter because "in practice, the Services often exempt habitat degradation from regulation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As a result, designating critical habitat has had limited regulatory effect." Overall, disagreement as to the effectiveness of critical habitat designation is expressed in a number of different reports.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Another controversy arises from the Act specifying that critical habitat designation is required to contain "all areas essential to the conservation" of the imperiled species, and may include private as well as public lands.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The Fish and Wildlife Service has a policy limiting designation to lands and waters within the U.S., and both federal agencies may exclude essential areas if they determine that economic or other costs exceed the benefit.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The ESA, however, is mute about how such costs and benefits are to be determined, and USFWS and NMFS have frequently minimized this exclusion provision's application in favor of large critical habitat designations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] All federal agencies are prohibited from authorizing, funding, or carrying out actions that "destroy or adversely modify" critical habitats (Section 7(a) (2)).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] While the regulatory aspect of critical habitat does not apply directly to private and other non-federal landowners, large-scale development, logging, and mining projects on private and state land typically require one or more federal permits and thus become subject to critical habitat regulations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Outside or in parallel with regulatory processes, critical habitats also focus and encourage voluntary actions such as land purchases, grant making, restoration, and establishment of reserves.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The Act's specification of the timing of critical habitat designations has also become problematic.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The ESA requires that critical habitat be designated at the time of or within one year of a species being placed on the endangered list.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In practice, most designations occur several years after listing.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Between 1978 and 1986, the FWS regularly designated critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 1986 the Reagan administration issued a regulation limiting the protective status of critical habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As a result, few critical habitats were designated between 1986 and the late 1990s.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, a series of court orders invalidated the Reagan regulations and forced the FWS and NMFS to designate several hundred critical habitats, especially in Hawaii, California, and other western states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Midwest and eastern states received less critical habitat, primarily on rivers and coastlines.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of December 2006, the Reagan regulation had not yet been replaced, though its use had been suspended.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Nonetheless, the agencies have generally changed course.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Since about 2005, both have tried to designate critical habitat at or near the time of listing.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The designation of critical habitat has proved to be one of the most controversial aspects of the ESA's administration.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] An example of such controversy can be found in *Weyerhaeuser Company v.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] United States Fish and Wildlife Service.* In this 2018 ruling, the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supreme Court addressed whether land can be designed as critical habitat even if the land cannot support the existence of protected species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The litigation arose over the designation of loblolly pine timberlands in Louisiana as critical habitat for the dusky gopher frog.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The plaintiffs objected to the designation of their land as critical habitat, citing its significant economic costs, including the inability to develop the land for commercial and residential uses.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Unanimously ruling for the property owners, the Supreme Court held that land cannot be designated as critical habitat if it cannot qualify as habitat.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The dusky gopher frog decision at the level of U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Supreme Court thus became a key species-specific example of the judiciary setting geographic boundaries on the agency's ability to designate critical habitat happened in 2018.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The court ruled as invalid the critical habitat designation of a segment of private timberlands in Louisiana in part because the endangered frog had been extirpated from that state for half a century, currently inhabiting only Mississippi.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Equally, it was clear that suitable pond "habitat" for the frog would require a degree of ecological restoration to be performed on the private land.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A 2020 law review article concluded that critical habitat designations were still far underutilized.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In 2005 the Center for Biological Diversity petitioned to list the polar bear as threatened, with critical habitat in Alaska.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Climate change was among the identified threats.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Rising temperatures and declining snowpack in the contiguous United States (not Alaska) had made cave denning difficult for the remaining populations in the Cascade Range and Rocky Mountains.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Because distinct populations of vertebrate species and subspecies can be listed, nine river systems where chinook salmon spawn are now protected under the Act (see image at right).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Salmon spawn in freshwater but mature in marine waters, so both the Fish and Wildlife Service and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration manage the listing and recovery actions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] While climate change was established in 2008 as a legitimate reason for listing a species, subspecies, or population, climate adaptation became an option for recovery actions only in 2023.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] This was when the geographic scope of the regulation pertaining to "**experimental populations**" was amended.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Although the Endangered Species Act of 1973 (as amended in 1982) did not in itself limit the placement of experimental populations to the "**historical range**" of a plant or animal, a regulatory change in 1984 made prospective translocations beyond the native range more difficult to justify.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Two Congressional Research Service reports focus on experimental populations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] One summarizes its early use for reasons other than climate change, and the other focuses on its past and present use in helping the gray wolf expand much farther into what had been its vast historical range.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As of February 2025, 64 species (including several populations of a single species) were listed as already having authorizations to implement "experimental populations." All can proceed on a "non-essential" basis (meaning, losses are expected but will not threaten the integrity of the gene pool).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The greatest number of authorizations apply to aquatic species (fishes, clams, mussels).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Two large and charismatic birds have been placed into locales far outside of where their last remnant populations survived prior to listing as endangered.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] These are the California condor and the Whooping crane.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Fish and Wildlife Service published a proposed rule in the *Federal Register* that would "revise section 10(j) regulations under the ESA to better facilitate recovery by allowing for the introduction of listed species to suitable habitats outside of their historical ranges.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] As reported on the news page of *Audubon*, adoption of the proposed regulatory change would authorize, for the first time, use of a controversial climate adaptation tool: assisted migration.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Department of Interior on June 30, 2023, announced its decision to modify the section 10(j) "experimental populations" rule generally as proposed a year earlier.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The press release summarized the reason for the change as, "At the time the original 10(j) regulations were established, the potential impact of climate change on species and their habitats was not fully realized, yet in the decades since have become even more dramatic.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The rulemaking action includes a section summarizing 25 topics entailed in comments submitted in 2022, along with the agency's official response to each.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Pre-existing requirements pertaining to experimental populations in the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) still apply.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Plans to use "Subpart H: experimental populations" for the purpose of climate change adaptation thus require public notice and ultimate placement in the "Species-specific rules" subpart of the CFR regulations of the precise geographic and other details.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Six months after this climate adaptation regulation for listed species was published, the National Park Service issued a 154-page report on recommendations for halting the decline of the endangered Karner blue butterfly in its small and scattered populations across the northeastern states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Among the recommendations were "managed relocation" of populations from the southern parts of its range into northward habitats with suitable conditions and supportive plants.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Two weeks after the 2024 United States presidential election, the founder of a citizen group, Torreya Guardians, urged the new administration to utilize the experimental populations regulation to recruit more citizens to help endangered plants.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The group had been using their own resources to do this for a critically endangered tree since 2008.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Utilizing an exception in the ESA just for plants, they had been experimentally planting **Florida torreya**, *Torreya taxifolia*, hundreds of miles northward of its native range (a glacial refugium) in Florida.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In October 2020, the Gray wolf (but not the Mexican wolf) was delisted by the federal government in all states.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Press releases by the FWS explained the scope and rationale of that action.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Several lawsuits challenging the delisting were filed in the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] District Court for the Northern District of California.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] A press release issued by one of the plaintiffs, Defenders of Wildlife, explained, "This decision made wolves vulnerable to hunting, trapping, poisoning, and other lethal controls.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The challenges continued after the report was published.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] In February 2022, the district court vacated and remanded the 2020 delisting rule.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] That decision reinstated the federal protections that were in place prior to the effective date of the 2020 delisting rule.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Gray wolves were thus once again listed as threatened in Minnesota and endangered in all or portions of 44 U.S. states and Mexico.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The regional exception where delisting was maintained spanned the 5 states where the Northern Rocky Mountain wolf population had established.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] The agency once again went to work on updating the **Species Status Assessment Report**, and creating a formal listing document plus a recovery plan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] House of Representatives passed a bill to delist the wolf that would override any decision by the agency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p03] Meanwhile the Nez Perce Tribe has been cooperating with federal authorities in wolf reintroduction on its own tribal lands in Idaho since the 1990s.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Nez Perce Tribe is not unusual in its respectful relationship to the wolf.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Another large predator species that has been fraught with ESA listing controversy for many years are the populations of grizzly bear outside of Alaska.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The grizzly, too, has a "species status assessment" prepared by the federal government.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Here, too, the Nez Perce Tribe is reported as prohibiting grizzly hunting on tribal lands.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The 398-page federal report does not, however, include any mention of traditional ecological knowledge pertaining to the bear.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The California legislature passed a bill to raise California regulations to thwart the Trump administration changes; it was vetoed by Governor Newsom.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In January 2020, the House Natural Resources Committee reported similar legislation.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In December 2020, the Trump administration further rolled back the Endangered Species Act by reducing habitat protections for at-risk species, and thus restricting protections to where they currently live—not where they lived previously or where they might migrate to as a result of climate change.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In June 2021, the Biden administration said it was reviewing the Trump era Endangered Species Act regulations and planned to reverse or revise some of the changes, in particular those relating to critical habitat regulations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] After a panel of the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals disallowed an initial attempt to immediately reverse these regulations in 2022, the Biden administration embarked on a rulemaking, and a series of less dramatic revisions were finalized in May 2024.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This regulatory flip-flop was not without precedent.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In March 2025 several conservation groups warned that numerous species currently listed could be driven to extinction as a result of the second Trump administration's mass firings of U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A representative of the group Earthjustice was quoted in the article as charging that the committee "can behave as god and decide what species exist and which don't." One year later, March 2026, the cabinet-level committee met for the first time in more than 30 years.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The greater-sage grouse is one declining species for which listing petitions have generated policy responses that flip-flop with presidential (and sometimes Congressional) election results.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Because the bird's sagebrush habitat ranges through ten western states and because much of that habitat is within the jurisdiction of the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Bureau of Land Management, the affected states have advocated for collaborative decision-making as a more malleable alternative to federal designation of the grouse as a threatened species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The first petition was submitted during the George W.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Bush administration, with policy deliberations carrying into President Obama's time in office during which a court order forced a decision on whether or not to list the bird as threatened.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] "Warranted but precluded" was the decision in 2010 that effectively pushed decision-making into an undetermined future time.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In April 2014, the Sage-Grouse and Endangered Species Conservation and Protection Act (H.R.4419) was passed in the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This statute prohibited the federal government from listing sage grouse under the Endangered Species Act for 10 years, so long as states prepared and carried out plans to protect the species within their borders.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A collaborative plan (without formal listing) was finally signed in 2015.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] It carried through the first Trump administration and into the Biden administration.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A few days after the 2024 election results determined that Donald J.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Trump would resume the presidency, the Biden administration offered an updated draft plan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Many national-level environmental groups communicated support for the plan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Several, however, pressed for the outgoing administration to formally list the species as threatened, thereby invoking more environmentally stringent decision-making on resource development proposals on federal lands, especially those administered by the U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Periodic "reauthorization" by Congress of the ESA of 1973 is a statutory requirement to ensure ongoing appropriations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Act was reauthorized for the first time in 1978 during the presidency of Jimmy Carter.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Reauthorization continued in 1982 and 1988 during the presidency of Ronald Reagan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Four years later another vote for renewal was due, but this did not occur.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] From 1992 on through at least 2024, reauthorization has never again been accomplished.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Mandatory funding for the law therefore expired in 1992.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Even so, partisan compromises that come from the necessity to annually pass an overall federal budget have maintained annual appropriations for continuing enforcement of the Act's provisions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A 2009 law review paper attributed increasing polarization in the "reauthorization debates" partly to the news media having incentives to attract readership by featuring the most dramatic quotations from "divergent narratives" that magnify the divide.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As well, interest groups on both sides "shared a perception that the ESA was broken." Because any move to reauthorize the Act would also open the prospect for amendment, "legislative gridlock and risk aversion on all political sides" restrain any serious effort to introduce a reauthorization bill.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Opening the Act itself to amendment by Congress has not been achieved in a major way since the amendments of 1988.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In December 2024, a substantial set of amendments was approved by the House Committee on Natural Resources, but nothing of similar scope moved through the Senate.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Nonetheless, Congressional interventions in executive branch implementation are regularly achieved via "riders" inserted into a multi-topic omnibus bill (notably, passage of the annual budget bill).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Very few of these moved out of any committee.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Most were attempts to block funding, overrule listing or delisting decisions, or alter regulations for just one species at a time.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Fish & Wildlife Service has developed a four-factor prioritization system for analyzing tradeoffs in distributing funds among the listed species: degree of threat, potential for recovery, taxonomic uniqueness, and conflict with human activities.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] As to the implementation of existing recovery plans, there is no requirement that federal agencies (or any other institution) implement any of the actions specified in those plans.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 1988, the 1973 Act was amended in several ways, including the creation of a new section.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The 2020 fiscal year report entailed many pages of tabulations.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One such list organized the species from the greatest to the least annual expenditures.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Chinook Salmon of Puget Sound was at the top of the list: $62 million.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] All but one of the 26 highest ranked species are fish that live, at least part of their lives, in freshwater habitats.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The one exception is also aquatic, but confined to marine waters and thus administered by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A reptile first shows up on the list as species rank 27.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] It is the desert tortoise, and its recovery actions entailed $8 million in 2020.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Next comes the manatee and soon thereafter the first birds: northern spotted owl and red-cockaded woodpecker.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Those were also in the $8 million range.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The grizzly bear is ranked 46, and it is in the $4 million range.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The first insect, Oregon silverspot butterfly is 139th on the list; its 2020 expenses were $737 thousand.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The American burying beetle is the next insect, at $673 thousand.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Costs escalated for the beetle when "**experimental populations**" were initiated in new locations beginning in 2011.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One has to scroll down to the 159th highest annual expenditure in order to find the first plant.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] It is a keystone species of coastal waters that provides expansive ecosystem services: seagrass.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Immediately following the seagrass is American crocodile and California condor.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] All three are just under $600 thousand apiece.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] At the opposite end of financial support are species that received the least in 2020.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Of the 1,599 domestic threatened and endangered species ranked in the long series of tables, 668 species were each allocated less than $10,000.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One plant, one fish, and one snail were in the lowest rank; each was managed with $100.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Cumulative expenditures in fiscal year 2020 for all 1,599 species were also calculated.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This compares to the 2018 fiscal year budget total of $1,269,621,055.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The reporting framework differs from year to year.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2018, the federal government cost for acquiring lands as critical habitat totaled $105,469,496, of which 45% came from the FWS agency budget and the rest from other federal sources.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Land acquisition expenditures, which may primarily come from the federal Land and Water Conservation Fund, were not included in the 2020 report.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Short reports on **agency requests for FY appropriations and Congressional deliberations thereof** are available for more recent years than the set of lengthy annual reports that documented actual agency expenditures from FY 1989 through 2020.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] For example, there is an online public narrative of the FY 2024 FWS request (with comparisons to 2022 and 2023).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The Congressional Research Service posted a short analysis of same.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] For FY 2024, there is also a lengthy report itemizing costs and requests for more than a dozen programs internal to FWS, but the endangered species program is not delineated among those programs, and there is no species-by-species accounting as had been the norm through 2020.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] A notable example happened in 1994 when the eastern North Pacific population of gray whale (which ranges along the west coast of North America) was delisted.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Its population had reached the recovery threshold, and henceforth the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972 was regarded as sufficient for maintaining that recovery into the future.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This also applied to delisting of the bald eagle in 2007, because DDT had been banned by the Environmental Protection Agency in 1972 and the Bald Eagle Protection Act had made killing of the bird illegal since 1940.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] What about species for whom active management had played a large role in bringing population numbers up to the recovery threshold, yet the threats that had been repelled by such management showed no prospect of going away?
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] In 2005 these kinds of species were labelled as conservation-reliant species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Accordingly, they would also be funding reliant — but not necessarily dependent on U.S.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Fish and Wildlife funding, nor possibly any other federal agency.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Instead, state agencies and sometimes non-governmental organizations would commit to maintaining the requisite conservation actions.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The authors concluded that "the challenge created by the conservation reliance of threatened and endangered species is formidable." This was based on a survey they conducted of the 1,361 existing recovery plans.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Fish and Wildlife Service and the National Marine Fisheries Service had begun using the concept of "conservation reliance" when planning and reporting efforts to recover and delist species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The statutory requirement for ensuring ongoing management by other institutions was achieved by securing management agreements with state governmental and also private entities (such as conservation organizations and conservation land trusts).
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] An example well-known for the number of institutions agreeing to bear responsibilities for continuing conservation actions pertains to the 2019 delisting of the Kirtland's warbler.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Designated as "endangered" in 1972 via the 1969 version of the endangered species statute, the warbler had dipped in population as low as 200 breeding pairs.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The initial recovery plan, as required by the 1973 statute, was published in 1976 and set a recovery goal of 1,000 breeding pairs.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] By then the science was clear as to what had been challenging the species for decades.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] One threat was habitat loss and the other was another species of bird.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Habitat loss is attributed to human interventions that severely reduced the scale and repetition of forest fires in the pine-rich ecosystems of northern Michigan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Kirtland's warblers will nest only in open woodlands dominated by jack pine, and only in the southernmost portion of the tree's otherwise vast range spanning far into Canada.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] But jack pine is an early successional species, and this means that canopy dominants, such as red pine, will eventually shade them out.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] And not just any jack pine can attract these birds to nest.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] There needs to be many of them, scaling to no less than several hundred acres of near monoculture.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Worse, prime habitat is naturally ephemeral.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Kirtland's warblers will nest only on the ground, and thus the protective trees have to be young enough (6 to 20 years old) for the lower branches to fully camouflage their chosen sites.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] But civilization cannot tolerate fires running rampant.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The species of bird that poses an equal threat was native to the prairie states — not the forests of Michigan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] This is the brown-headed cowbird, which had evolved a clever way to raise its young while harvesting insects lofted by roaming herds of bison.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] They had become brood parasites, laying their eggs in the nests of other bird species.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] But the bison are gone, and cattle and farm fields have replaced much of the forest in Michigan.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] The cowbirds easily adapted to this new landscape, laying their eggs deliberately in the nests of smaller-bodied birds.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Cowbird hatchlings are much bigger than the rightful occupants of the nest, easily pushing them out and also reaching higher to snatch food from the bills of the foster parents.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Active, ongoing management is thus unavoidable.
[src:endangered-species-act-of-1973/endangered-species-act-of-1973-p04] Controlled burns or jack pine harvests need to be repeated throughout the dedicated and acquired habitat.
